UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<div><strong>Control Objective</strong></div>&#10;<div class="mb-2">&#10;  <ol type="a">&#10;   <li>Develop, document, and disseminate to [Assignment: organization-defined personnel or roles]:&#10;    <ol>&#10;      <li>[Selection (one or more): Organization-level; Mission/business process-level; System-level] awareness and training&#10;        policy that:&#10;      <ol type="a">&#10;        <li>Addresses purpose, scope, roles, responsibilities, management commitment, coordination among organizational&#10;          entities, and compliance</li>&#10;          <li>Is consistent with applicable laws, executive orders, directives, regulations, policies, standards, and&#10;            guidelines</li>&#10;      </ol>&#10;      </li>&#10;      <li> Procedures to facilitate the implementation of the awareness and training policy and the associated awareness and&#10;        training controls;</li>&#10;    </ol>&#10;   </li>&#10;   <li> Designate an [Assignment: organization-defined official] to manage the development, documentation, and&#10;    dissemination of the awareness and training policy and procedures;</li>&#10;    <li>Review and update the current awareness and training:&#10;      </li><li>Policy [Assignment: organization-defined frequency] and following [Assignment: organization-defined events]</li>&#10;      <li> Procedures [Assignment: organization-defined frequency] and following [Assignment: organization-defined events].</li>&#10;    &#10;  </ol>&#10;&#10;</div><div><strong>Supplemental Guidance</strong></div><div class="mb-2">Awareness and training policy and procedures address the controls in the AT family that are implemented within systems and organizations. The risk management strategy is an important factor in establishing such policies and procedures. Policies and procedures contribute to security and privacy assurance. Therefore, it is important that security and privacy programs collaborate on the development of awareness and training policy and procedures.&#160;</div><div class="mb-2">Security and privacy program policies and procedures at the organization level are preferable, in general, and may obviate the need for mission- or system-specific policies and procedures. The policy can be included as part of the general security and privacy policy or be represented by multiple policies that reflect the complex nature of organizations. Procedures can be established for security and privacy programs, for mission or business processes, and for systems, if needed. Procedures describe how the policies or controls are implemented and can be directed at the individual or role that is the object of the procedure.&#160;</div><div class="mb-2">Procedures can be documented in system security and privacy plans or in one or more separate documents. Events that may precipitate an update to awareness and training policy and procedures include assessment or audit findings, security incidents or breaches, or changes in applicable laws, executive orders, directives, regulations, policies, standards, and guidelines. Simply restating controls does not constitute an organizational policy or procedure.</div><div><strong>For further information, see related controls</strong></div><div class="mb-2">PM-9, PS-8, SI-12.</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 5267
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<div><strong>Control Objective</strong></div>&#10;<div class="mb-2">&#10;  <ol type="a">&#10;    <li>Provide role-based security and privacy training to personnel with the following roles and&#10;      responsibilities: [Assignment: organization-defined roles and responsibilities]:&#10;    <ol>&#10;      <li>Before authorizing access to the system, information, or performing assigned duties, and [Assignment:&#10;        organization-defined frequency] thereafter</li>&#10;        <li>When required by system changes;</li>&#10;    </ol>&#10;  </li>&#10;<li>Update role-based training content [Assignment: organization-defined frequency] and following [Assignment:&#10;  organization-defined events]</li>&#10;  <li>Incorporate lessons learned from internal or external security incidents or breaches into role-based training.</li>&#10;  </ol>&#10;&#10;</div><div><strong>Supplemental Guidance</strong></div><div class="mb-2">Organizations determine the content of training based on the assigned roles and responsibilities of individuals as well as the security and privacy requirements of organizations and the systems to which personnel have authorized access, including technical training specifically tailored for assigned duties. Roles that may require role-based training include senior leaders or management officials (e.g., head of agency/chief executive officer, chief information officer, senior accountable official for risk management, senior agency information security officer, senior agency official for privacy), system owners; authorizing officials; system security officers; privacy officers; acquisition and procurement officials; enterprise architects; systems engineers; software developers; systems security engineers; privacy engineers; system, network, and database administrators; auditors; personnel conducting configuration management activities; personnel performing verification and validation activities; personnel with access to system-level software; control assessors; personnel with contingency planning and incident response duties; personnel with privacy management responsibilities; and personnel with access to personally identifiable information.&#160;</div><div class="mb-2">Comprehensive role-based training addresses management, operational, and technical roles and responsibilities covering physical, personnel, and technical controls. Role-based training also includes policies, procedures, tools, methods, and artifacts for the security and privacy roles defined. Organizations provide the training necessary for individuals to fulfill their responsibilities related to operations and supply chain risk management within the context of organizational security and privacy programs.&#160;</div><div class="mb-2">Role-based training also applies to contractors who provide services to federal agencies. Types of training include web-based and computer-based training, classroom-style training, and hands-on training (including micro-training). Updating role-based training on a regular basis helps to ensure that the content remains relevant and effective. Events that may precipitate an update to role-based training content include, but are not limited to, assessment or audit findings, security incidents or breaches, or changes in applicable laws, executive orders, directives, regulations, policies, standards, and guidelines.</div><div><strong>For further information, see related controls</strong></div><div class="mb-2">AC-3, AC-17, AC-22, AT-2, AT-4, CP-3, IR-2, IR-4, IR-7, IR-9, PL-4, PM-13, PM-23, PS-7, PS-9, SA-3, SA-8, SA-11, SA-16, SR-5, SR-6, SR-11.</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 5268
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<div><strong>Control Objective</strong></div>&#10;<div class="mb-2">&#10;  <ol type="a">&#10;    <li> Provide security and privacy literacy training to system users (including managers, senior&#10;      executives, and contractors):&#10;      <ol>&#10;        <li>As part of initial training for new users and [Assignment: organization-defined frequency]</li>&#10;        <li>When required by system changes or following [Assignment: organization-defined events];</li>&#10;      </ol>&#10;    </li>&#10;&#10;    <li> Employ the following techniques to increase the security and privacy awareness of system users [Assignment:&#10;      organization-defined awareness techniques].</li>&#10;    <li>When required by system changes or following [Assignment: organization-defined events];</li>&#10;    <li>Update literacy training and awareness content [Assignment: organization-defined frequency] and following&#10;      [Assignment: organization-defined events]</li>&#10;    <li>Incorporate lessons learned from internal or external security incidents or breaches into literacy training and&#10;      awareness techniques.</li>&#10;  </ol>&#10;&#10;</div><div><strong>Supplemental Guidance</strong></div><div class="mb-2">Organizations provide basic and advanced levels of literacy training to system users, including measures to test the knowledge level of users. Organizations determine the content of literacy training and awareness based on specific organizational requirements, the systems to which personnel have authorized access, and work environments (e.g., telework). The content includes an understanding of the need for security and privacy as well as actions by users to maintain security and personal privacy and to respond to suspected incidents.&#160;</div><div class="mb-2">The content addresses the need for operations security and the handling of personally identifiable information.&#10;Awareness techniques include displaying posters, offering supplies inscribed with security and privacy reminders, displaying logon screen messages, generating email advisories or notices from organizational officials, and conducting awareness events. Literacy training after the initial training described in AT-2a.1 is conducted at a minimum frequency consistent with applicable laws, directives, regulations, and policies.&#160;</div><div class="mb-2">Subsequent literacy training may be satisfied by one or more short ad hoc sessions and include topical information on recent attack schemes, changes to organizational security and privacy policies, revised security and privacy expectations, or a subset of topics from the initial training. Updating literacy training and awareness content on a regular basis helps to ensure that the content remains relevant. Events that may precipitate an update to literacy training and awareness content include, but are not limited to, assessment or audit findings, security incidents or breaches, or changes in applicable laws, executive orders, directives, regulations, policies, standards, and guidelines.</div><div><strong>For further information, see related controls</strong></div><div class="mb-2">AC-3, AC-17, AC-22, AT-3, AT-4, CP-3, IA-4, IR-2, IR-7, IR-9, PL-4, PM-13, PM-21, PS-7, PT-2, SA-8, SA-16.</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 5269
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Recovery plans that are not regularly exercised may not be able to be executed in a timely or complete manner consistent with the intent of the recovery plans.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>The goal of this question is to determine if the plans provide sufficient process direction to be fully executed to achieve the recovery time and point objectives.</p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Exercised plans are executed in accordance with the plans themselves.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Plan exists</li>&#10;    <li>Plan is regularly evaluated and updated as needed</li>&#10;    <li>Plan is regularly exercised to ensure operational capability</li>&#10;    <li>Recovery exercises are completed in full accordance with the tested plan</li>&#10;    <li>Tested plan achieves recovery time objective as stated in the plan</li>&#10;    <li>Tested plan achieves recovery point objective as stated in the plan</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Failure to meet recovery time or point objectives;&#160;<br>&#160;OR</li>&#10;    <li>Incomplete direction within the plan to facilitate execution</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Recovery plan(s), evidence of recovery plan reviews and updates</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 CP-2, CP-4(4)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6201
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> The review of executed service continuity plans identifies plan shortcomings and needed improvements.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>To determine if the execution of service continuity plans is reviewed.</p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Unforeseen circumstances that arise during the execution are to be documented and addressed.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><em><span>&#160;</span></em><strong><u>The execution of each service continuity plan</u></strong> that supports the critical service is reviewed.<br>&#160;OR</li>&#10;    <li><em><span>&#160;</span></em>I<strong><u>f service continuity plans have not been executed</u></strong>, reviews of executed plans are required as part of a standard process.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The execution of some service continuity plans is reviewed.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>A formal report or correspondence that demonstrates service continuity plans have been reviewed.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>CRR, SCM:G4.Q2</li>&#10;    <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 IR-4, IR-4(3)</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6202
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> As systems evolve so too must plans designed to provide continuity of service capabilities. Without current service continuity plans, the organization may not be able to ensure the recovery of mission-essential services.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question is presented to ascertain the current relevance of documented service continuity plans and to determine if improvements are identified as a result of executing service continuity plans.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>As a result of the review of executed service continuity plans areas of improvement are identified, captured, and documented.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Typical work products include:</span></li>&#10;    <li>list of improvements to service continuity plans</li>&#10;    <li>list of improvements to service continuity test plans</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for &#8220;Yes&#8221; Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Improvements to each executed service continuity plan that supports the critical service are identified and documented.<br>&#160;OR</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>If service continuity plans have not been executed, the identification of improvements to executed plans is required as part of a standard process.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for &#8220;Incomplete&#8221; Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Improvements to some executed service continuity plans are identified and documented.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>C<span>hange management documentation for service continuity plans</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>CRR: SCM:G4.Q3</li>&#10;    <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 IR-4</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6203
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Comparison of implementation test results is used to identify gaps and track the improvement of the service continuity plan over the life of a given system.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>To determine if test results are compared to test objectives to identify improvements to recovery and service continuity plans. Improvements to the plans are driven by objective evaluation of the systems over time.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Regular testing and exercise of the service continuity plans:&#160;</span>The objective of service continuity plan testing is to ensure that plans work as intended.</li>&#10;    <li>Testing identifies required improvements to the service continuity plans as well as the associated test plans.</li>&#10;    <li>The evaluation of test results involves comparing the documented test results against the established test objectives.</li><li>Areas, where objectives could not be met, are recorded, and strategies are developed to review and revise the plans.</li>&#10;    <li>Improvements to the testing process and plans should also be identified, documented, and incorporated into future tests.</li>&#10;    <li><span>Examples of clearly defined test objectives include; MTTR, RPO, RTO, etc.</span></li>&#10;    <li>Improvement Areas may include:</li><li><span>lack of sufficient resources</span><br></li>&#10;    <li>lack of appropriate resources</li>&#10;    <li>training gaps for plan staff and stakeholders</li>&#10;    <li>plan conflicts (if multiple plans are tested simultaneously)</li>&#10;    <li>required changes to infrastructure</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><em><span>&#183;&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;</span></em>Test results for each service continuity plan required for the delivery of the critical service are compared with test objectives to identify needed improvements.</li>&#10;    <li><em><span>&#183;&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;</span></em>The system will be considered to have fully addressed this question if established baselines, previous test results, and clear testing objectives are documented and used to improve the service continuity plans.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><em><span>&#183;&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;</span></em>Test results for some service continuity plans are compared with test objectives to identify needed improvements. <span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>D<span>ocumented test results, list of improvements to service continuity plans, list of improvements to service continuity test plans</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>CRR: SCM:G3.Q5</li>&#10;    <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 Q5, IR-8</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6204
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Appropriate communications to external stakeholders is an important element in managing the impact of a cybersecurity incident. Timely updates and a conveyed impression of transparency can help defuse tensions that may build as a result of an incident.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>To determine if incident status and response are communicated to public relations staff and external media outlets.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Incident status and response should be communicated in a controlled and regular manner to internal and external stakeholders.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Incident status and response should be managed throughout the incident lifecycle.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>The incident communication process should include:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>the stakeholders with whom communication about incidents is required</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>the level of communication appropriate to various stakeholders</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>special controls over communication (i.e., encryption or secured communications) that are appropriate for some stakeholders</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>the frequency and timing of communication</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>Examples of stakeholders that may need to be included in incident communication:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>internal staff who have incident handling and management responsibilities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>asset owners and service owners</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>information technology staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>business continuity staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>affected customers or suppliers</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>local, state, and federal emergency management staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>support functions such as legal, audit, and human resources</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>legal and law enforcement staff (including federal agencies) if the incident may have legal ramifications</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>external media outlets</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>regulatory and governing agencies</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>local utilities (power, gas, telecommunications, water, etc.)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for &#8220;Yes&#8221; Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization communicates incident status and response to all public relations staff and external media outlets.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for &#8220;Incomplete&#8221; Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization communicates incident status and response to some public relations staff and external media outlets. (Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence:</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Organization-level communications plan</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Incident communications plan</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Example of past communications</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>CRR IM:G4.Q3</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6205
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Cybersecurity incidents can damage the reputation of an organization or critical service, thereby undermining its effectiveness. The presence of plans to repair its reputation will allow an organization to begin that work more quickly after an incident occurs, thus minimizing the long-term impact of an incident.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>To determine whether an organization&#8217;s recovery plans include measures to repair the reputation of an organization or service following a cybersecurity incident.</p>&#10;<p><span>Reputation should be interpreted broadly and could include the standing of an organization or service with the general public, other departments within the organization, government agencies, or commercial entities, to name just a few examples.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The plans need not detail every potential contingency and stakeholder but should be sufficient to guide activities in a meaningful way.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><em><span>&#160;</span></em><span>Recovery plans include measures to repair reputation with all primary stakeholders in anticipated incident scenarios.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Recovery plans include a measure to repair reputation with some primary stakeholders or some anticipated scenarios. (Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Incident response plan</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Organization-level communications plan</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Incident communications plan</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Disaster recovery plan</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Business continuity plan</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>NIST CSF RC.CO-2,&#160;</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 <span>IR-4(15)</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6206
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Providing appropriate information to internal and external stakeholders can reduce confusion and enhance reputation during security incidents and recovery activities. The communications plan helps ensure that the proper resources are available when needed and that individuals know their roles.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>To determine if there is a documented communications plan associated with incident management and recovery activities.</p>&#10;<p><span>While the communications plan need not identify all possible contingencies, it does need to include a complete work breakdown structure that documents responsibilities, stakeholders, and core activities. It should be sufficiently detailed to ensure duplicative work does not occur and that there is clarity for who is communicating to which stakeholders.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The plan should provide information on what to communicate, when to communicate it, to whom the communication should be directed, who shall do the communication and the methods by which communication shall occur.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><em><span>&#160;</span></em><span>Communications plans include both incident management and recovery as well as all primary stakeholders and work roles.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>&#160;Communications plans are present but lack detail on either incident management or recovery scenarios, stakeholders, or work roles. (Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Incident response plan</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Organization-level communications plan</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Incident communications plan</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Disaster recovery plan</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Business continuity plan</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>ISO/IEC 27001:2013, 7.4 Communication,&#160;</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 <span>CP-2, IR-4</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6207
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizations have many types of stakeholders that require communications related to managing incidents and recovery activities. These stakeholders may be very diverse depending on the type of communications needs they have, the frequency of the communications (whether discrete or continuous, circumstantial, or ongoing), and the level of communications necessary (notifications, press releases, crisis communications, etc.). Understanding the level and extent of stakeholders helps the organization to effectively develop and satisfy communications requirements.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>To determine whether the organization has identified the internal and external stakeholders with whom communication must occur during incident management and recovery activities.</p>&#10;<p><span>Internal stakeholders are identified to ensure ongoing communication about the organization&#8217;s activities, promote awareness, and ensure that staff can effectively communicate and collaborate during disruptive events. Likewise, external stakeholders may need information about the organization&#8217;s incident response, or they may have to be able to effectively communicate with the organization during times of crisis. These external organizations may even have a stated role in the communications plans or the service continuity of the organization. In addition, some regulatory and legal entities may require ongoing communications as evidence that an organization has taken appropriate actions to prepare for specific threats such as natural disasters and terrorism. Thus, the list of external stakeholders is developed to ensure proactive communications and message delivery regarding the organization&#8217;s preparedness and capabilities for managing incidents and recovery.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Because there are many stakeholders that require information, the organization must identify the relevant stakeholders and distribute information about communications plans to them as necessary. These stakeholders will have a&#160;</span>vested interest or vital role&#160;in communications about incident management and recovery activities.</p>&#10;<p><span>When determining which stakeholders to include in the list, consider</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>rationale for stakeholder involvement</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>roles and responsibilities of the relevant stakeholders</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>relationships between stakeholders</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>relative importance of the stakeholder to the success of the program</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>resources (e.g., training, materials, time, and funding) needed to ensure stakeholder interaction</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><strong><span>All primary stakeholders</span></strong><span>&#160;requiring communications are identified and <strong>formally documented</strong>.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><strong><span>Some primary stakeholders</span></strong><span>&#160;requiring communications are identified and <strong>formally documented</strong>. (Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>List of stakeholders that need to receive communications</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Classes or roles of stakeholders</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>List of appropriate internal and external stakeholders</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Stakeholder involvement plan</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>CERT RMM COMM:SG1.SP1</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6208
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizations must understand stakeholder needs if they are to write successful incident management and recovery communications plans. This detailed understanding will help organizations select the appropriate method, frequency, and level of detail associated with communications.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>The foundation for communications requirements is the needs of stakeholders. The variety of communication types and duration are directly related to the diversity of the stakeholder community. For example, internal communication might be about general awareness or a specific event or incident. External communications might be public relations messages, critical communications during a crisis, or the execution of a service continuity plan.</p>&#10;<p><span>In addition to stakeholders, communications requirements may also be derived directly from the needs of other operational resilience management processes. For example, the ways in which the organization must distribute the information collected in the monitoring process may create requirements that must be met by the communications process.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The organization must establish communications requirements as the foundation for the development and execution of a communications plan to support incident management and recovery activities. Requirements help the organization determine the scope of the communications process, plan, and program and ensure the development of appropriate and cost-effective delivery mechanisms and infrastructure to support communications needs. Requirements determine whether communications methods are:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>oral or written, or both</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>provided on a one-time basis, at regular intervals, on an ongoing basis, or on demand</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>provided on media that are disposable or able to be archived</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>provided on more than one media type (paper, electronic, etc.)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>Communications requirements also provide the foundation for the development and implementation of an infrastructure (people, processes, and technology) to support all types of resilience communication.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><strong><span>All stakeholder</span></strong><span>&#160;incident response and recovery communications <strong>needs are identified</strong>.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><strong><span>Some stakeholder</span></strong><span>&#160;incident response and recovery communications <strong>needs are identified</strong> conditions that constitute an Incomplete. (Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Communications requirements by stakeholders and process</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>CERT RMM COMM:SG1.SP2</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6209
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> The diverse and expansive nature of communications requirements for supporting Incident management and recovery processes requires knowledgeable, skilled, and experienced staff to be successful.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>To determine if the organization&#8217;s communications plans associated with incident management and recovery include staffing that is formally assigned and held accountable for its performance.</p>&#10;<p><span>Resources must be available in the organization to staff or support all types of communications as needed. Internal communications and public relations activities tend to be carried out by communications professionals&#8212;staff who have specific training and skills in communications and who work primarily in communications roles in the organization. Notification, escalation, and coordination of communications may be carried out by anyone in the organization who is in a primary or supporting incident response or recovery management role. Thus, staff on an incident response team may be involved in communications roles because of the nature of their work. These types of communications are typically supported by a communications infrastructure and knowledgeable staff who support the infrastructure or are trained in effective communications during times of stress and disruption.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Regardless of the type of the communication, the organization must provide training (sometimes specialized) to staff who support and enable communications processes. This may begin with a skills inventory and gap analysis so that effective training programs can be identified and used. For staff involved in communications roles during the execution of service continuity plans, communications training may be extensive and may involve frequent exercises and tests to ensure effectiveness.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Communication resources may be internal or external to the organization. Thus, where the organization does not have direct control over communications resources, it must attempt to ensure that proper training is provided to carry out plan and program requirements.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><strong><span>All staff required</span></strong><span>&#160;for incident and recovery communications have their authority, responsibilities, and accountability <strong>formally documented</strong>.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Some staff required for incident and recovery communications are documented, or their authority, responsibility, and accountability information is incomplete. (Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Job descriptions for roles and responsibilities in the plan</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>List of available and skilled resources</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>List of skill and resource gaps</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Mitigation plans to address skill and resource gaps</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Updated communications plan with resources assigned</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>CERT RMM COMM:SG2.SP3</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6210
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> The methods and channels that the organization chooses for communications regarding incident response and recovery must be able to support and enable communications requirements as stated in the communications plan and program.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>To determine if the communications methods and channels related to incident response and recovery are identified and appropriate to the needs of the organization and its stakeholders.</p>&#10;<p><span>Communication methods and channels may be formal or informal, oral, or&#160;</span>written, peer-to-peer, peer-to-subordinate, or peer-to-superior. Messages can also be delivered non-verbally through actions and gestures. Communications methods and channels can include:</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>policy statements</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>procedures manuals and company handbooks</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>specific press releases and wires</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>company hotlines, such as those that allow for reporting of ethics violations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>email messages and text messaging</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>intranet and internet sites and webcasts</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>newsletters, posters, and flyers, as well as bulletin boards and other gathering spots</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>newspapers, magazines, and other print media</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>television, radio, podcasts, videocasts, and other public media</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>presentations, tutorials, and symposia</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>emergency broadcast systems and methods</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>closed communications channels such as two-way radio, CB radio, and satellite phone</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>secured communications channels (to provide for classified conversations) such as STUs (secure telephone units)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>Methods and tools for communicating with staff, customers, end users, service provider staff, and other stakeholders during the course of service delivery are also part of the enterprise-wide communications strategy and execution. These methods and tools have to be regularly reviewed, tailored, and possibly supplemented to meet ongoing communications requirements.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has documented <strong>all communications channels</strong> and methods required for incident response and recovery communications.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><em><span>&#160;</span></em><span>The organization has documented <strong>some of the communications channels</strong> and methods required for incident response and recovery communications. (Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Documented communications methods and channels (by stakeholder class or requirement)</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Tools, techniques, and methods for communication</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>CERT RMM COMM:SG3.SP1</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6211
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> A deny-all, permit-by-exception network communications traffic policy ensures that only those system connections that are essential and approved are allowed.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> To determine if the use of allow-lists is implemented to restrict communications with the critical service/HVA environment to a specified set of addresses.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Ensure that cyber resources are used consistently with the mission or business function purposes and approved uses. Avoid &#8220;mission creep,&#8221; which can increase a system&#8217;s attack surface.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Identify IP addresses/ranges authorized to communicate with the system.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow communications with authorized IP addresses/ranges.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Denying by default and allowing by exception applies to inbound and outbound network communications traffic.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>General source address validation techniques are applied to restrict the use of illegal and unallocated source addresses as well as source addresses that should only be used within the system.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Review and update the list of authorized IP addresses/ranges at an organization-defined frequency.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Allow-lists have been implemented on all appropriate technology assets to restrict communications with the critical service/HVA environment to a specified set of addresses.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Allow-lists have been implemented on some appropriate technology assets to restrict communications with the critical service/HVA environment to a specified set of addresses.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Documented allow-lists that have been implemented on all appropriate technology assets or system components.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Documentation detailing the implementation and configuration of the allow-lists on all appropriate technology assets or system components.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 <span>CM-7(5), SC-7(5), SC-7(11)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6212
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Ensuring there is a mission or business reason for trusting a resource prevents the associated trustworthiness from being inadvertently diminished and may prevent the trust from being consequently misplaced.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> To determine if the process for designating a resource (such as a workstation, network, application, database, etc.) as trusted ensures that a mission or business reason exists to justify the designation.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Trustworthiness:</span></strong> Worthy of being trusted to fulfill whatever critical requirements may be needed for a particular component, subsystem, system, network, application, mission, business function, enterprise, or other entity.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Ensure that cyber resources are used consistently with the mission or business function purposes and approved uses. Avoid &#8220;mission creep,&#8221; which can increase a system&#8217;s attack surface.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>The principle of trusted components states that a component is trustworthy to at least a level commensurate with the security dependencies it supports (i.e., how much it is trusted to perform its security functions by other components).</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Trustworthiness requirements can include attributes of safety, security, reliability, dependability, performance, resilience, and survivability under a wide range of potential adversity in the form of disruptions, hazards, and threats.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>A process for designating a critical service/HVA resource as trusted has been implemented and documented.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>The process ensures that there is a mission or business reason that justifies the designation of trusted.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>A process for designating a critical service/HVA resource as trusted is in development and partially documented.<br><strong>&#160;OR</strong></span></li>&#10;    <li><span>The process is implemented but does not always ensure that there is a mission or business reason that justifies the designation of trusted.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>A documented process for designating a critical service/HVA resource as trusted and ensuring that there is a mission or business reason that justifies the designation of trusted.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Documented outcomes of the process detailing the evaluation and mission/business reason for the designation of trusted.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 <span>SA-8(9)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6213
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong>Importance:</strong><span> Ensuring that cyber resources are used consistently with the mission or business function purposes and approved uses will help avoid mission/scope creep which can increase a system&#8217;s attack surface.</span><br></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> To determine if there is an implemented process to analyze system components and ensure that the information resources are being used consistent with their intended purpose.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Ensure that cyber resources are used consistently with the mission or business function purposes and approved uses. Avoid &#8220;mission creep,&#8221; which can increase a system&#8217;s attack surface.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Systems are designed to support a specific mission or business function. However, over time, systems and system components may be used to support services and functions that are outside of the scope of the intended mission or business functions.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>This mission or scope creep can result in exposing information resources to unintended environments and uses that can significantly increase threat exposure.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Exposing information resources to unintended environments and uses may make the systems more vulnerable to compromise, which can ultimately impact the services and functions for which they were intended.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>By analyzing information resource use, organizations can identify such potential exposures.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A process to analyze critical service/HVA system components to ensure all information resources are being used consistent with their intended purpose has been implemented and documented.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A process to analyze critical service/HVA system components to ensure all information resources are being used consistent with their intended purpose is in development and partially documented.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>A documented process to analyze critical service/HVA system components to ensure all information resources are being used consistent with their intended purpose.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Documented outcomes of the process detailing analysis and the associated results.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 PM-32</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6214
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:&#160;</span></strong>Criticality analysis is a key risk management tenant and informs the prioritization of critical mission-critical services/functions, associated systems, and system components, and informs the prioritization of protection and sustainment requirements and activities.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>To determine if a criticality analysis of the critical service/HVA environment has been completed and as a result, the critical system components and functions have been identified and documented.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Not all system components, functions, or services necessarily require significant protections.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>The identification of critical system components and functions considers applicable laws, executive orders, regulations, directives, policies, standards, system functionality requirements, system and component interfaces, and system and component dependencies.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Systems engineers conduct a functional decomposition of a system to identify mission-critical functions and components. The functional decomposition includes the identification of organizational missions supported by the system, decomposition into the specific functions to perform those missions, and traceability to the hardware, software, and firmware components that implement those functions, including when the functions are shared by many components within and external to the system.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>The operational environment of a system or a system component may impact the criticality, including the connections to and dependencies on cyber-physical systems, devices, system-of-systems, and outsourced IT services.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>System components that allow unmediated access to critical system components or functions are considered critical due to the inherent vulnerabilities that such components create.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Component and function criticality are assessed in terms of the impact of a component or function failure on the organizational missions that are supported by the system that contains the components and functions.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Criticality analysis is performed when architecture or design is being developed, modified, or upgraded.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>If such analysis is performed early in the system development life cycle, organizations may be able to modify the system design to reduce the critical nature of these components and functions, such as by adding redundancy or alternate paths into the system design.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>In addition to criticality analysis for systems, system components, and system services, criticality analysis of information is an important consideration.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has completed and documented the results of a criticality analysis and as an outcome identified all critical system components and functions of the critical service/HVA environment.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization is in the process of performing a criticality analysis and has partially documented the results.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Documented results from the criticality analysis detailing the identified critical system components and functions.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 <span>RA-9</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6215
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> <span>A policy establishes and communicates the organizational expectations for planning and governing the outsourcing of essential and nonessential functions to the organization</span>.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> To determine if a policy that governs outsourcing of essential and nonessential functions exists.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>A <strong>policy&#160;</strong>is written communication from the organization&#8217;s senior management to employees.</li>&#10;    <li>It establishes the organizational expectations for planning and governing the outsourcing of essential and nonessential functions and communicates those expectations to the organization.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>The policy should address<strong><span>:</span></strong></span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>responsibility, authority, ownership, and the requirement to perform outsourcing activities</li>&#10;    <li>establishment of procedures, standards, and guidelines</li>&#10;    <li>establishing and maintaining the outsourcing relationship</li>&#10;    <li>governing the outsourcing of essential and nonessential functions</li>&#10;    <li>measuring adherence to policy, exceptions granted, and policy violations</li>&#10;    <li>compliance with legal, regulatory, contractual, and government obligations</li>&#10;    <li>Offload supportive but nonessential functions to other systems or to an external provider that is better able to perform the functions securely</li>&#10;    <li>Offloading reduces the attack surface and motivates ongoing consideration of what is essential.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a documented policy for governing the outsourcing of essential and nonessential functions.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A policy is in development and partially documented.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A documented policy for governing the outsourcing of essential and nonessential functions.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments:</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 <span>PM-7(1)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6216
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Maintaining such functions on the same primary systems or system components increases the attack surface of the organization&#8217;s mission-essential functions or services.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent</span></strong>: To determine if the organization offloads or outsources nonessential services to a managed service provider.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Offload supportive but nonessential functions to other systems or to an external provider that is better able to perform the functions securely</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Offloading reduces the attack surface and motivates ongoing consideration of what is essential.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Not every function or service that a system provides is essential to the organizational mission or business functions. General printing or copying is an example of a non-essential but supporting service for an organization.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Whenever feasible, such supportive but non-essential functions or services are<strong>&#160;not&#160;</strong>co-located with the functions or services that support the essential mission or business functions.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Maintaining nonessential functions on the same system or system component increases the attack surface of the organization&#8217;s mission-essential functions or services.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Moving supportive but non-essential functions to a non-critical system, system component, or external provider can also increase efficiency by putting those functions or services under the control of individuals or providers who are subject matter experts in the functions or services.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The organization has determined which functions or services are considered nonessential.<br>&#160;AND</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>The organization has outsourced all of the applicable nonessential functions or services to a managed service provider.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The organization is in the process of determining which functions or services are considered nonessential.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or the organization has determined which functions or services are considered nonessential and is in the process of outsourcing all of the applicable nonessential functions or services to a managed service provider.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>A documented list of which functions or services the organization has determined to be nonessential</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>An agreement with a managed service provider showing their management of the applicable nonessential functions or services.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 <span>PM-7(1)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6217
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> The responsibility for managing risks from the use of external system services remains with the organization&#8217;s authorizing officials.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> To determine if (1) the organization requires providers of external system services to comply with organizational requirements and (2) if the organization performs oversight of those services.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Require that providers of external system services comply with organizational security and privacy requirements.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Define and document organizational oversight and user roles and responsibilities with regard to external system services.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>External system services are provided by an external provider, and the organization has no direct control over the implementation of the required controls or the assessment of control effectiveness.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>For services external to organizations, a chain of trust requires that organizations establish and retain a certain level of confidence that each provider in the consumer-provider relationship provides adequate protection for the services rendered.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Organizations document the basis for the trust relationships so that the relationships can be monitored.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>External system services documentation includes government, service providers, user-end-user security roles and responsibilities, and service-level agreements.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Service-level agreements define the expectations of performance for implemented controls, describe measurable outcomes, and identify remedies and response requirements for identified instances of noncompliance.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The organization has imposed documented requirements on all appropriate external system services.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>And the organization performs oversight of all appropriate external system services.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The organization is in the process of imposing documented requirements on all appropriate external system services.&#160;<br><strong>&#160;OR</strong></span></li>&#10;    <li><span>The organization is in the process of documenting requirements for the appropriate external system services.&#160;<br>&#160;<strong>OR</strong></span></li>&#10;    <li><span>The organization is in the process of establishing oversight of all appropriate external system services.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Documented organizational oversight and user roles and responsibilities with regard to external system services.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Documented requirements that external service providers must comply with.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Agreements with the external providers that define performance expectations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Documented results from the review of external provider performance.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments:</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 <span>SA-9</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6218
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:&#160;</span></strong>The use of obsolete, nearing obsolete, or low assurance implementations of technology may increase the security and privacy risks.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>To determine if the organization replaces obsolete and unsupported system components as needed and prior to the end of support or service agreements.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Replace low-assurance or poorly understood implementations with trustworthy implementations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Technology refresh planning may encompass hardware, software, firmware, processes, personnel skill sets, suppliers, service providers, and facilities.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Technology refreshes typically occur during the operations and maintenance stage of the system development life cycle.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>The use of obsolete or nearing obsolete technology may increase the security and privacy risks associated with:</span></li>&#10;    <li>unsupported components</li>&#10;    <li>counterfeit or repurposed components</li>&#10;    <li>components unable to implement security or privacy requirements</li>&#10;    <li>slow or inoperable components</li>&#10;    <li>components from untrusted sources</li>&#10;    <li>inadvertent personnel error</li>&#10;    <li>or increased complexity</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization replaces all system components designated as obsolete or unsupported prior to the end of support or service level agreements.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization replaces some system components designated as obsolete or unsupported prior to the end of support or service level agreements.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>A documented list or inventory of system components considered to be obsolete or unsupported</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Updated inventory showing replacement components and updated asset descriptions.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Copies of support or service level agreements showing the term of the agreement.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 <span>SA-3(3)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6219
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:&#160;</span></strong>Attack surfaces review enables personnel to understand and address the systems and system components that present exposed areas that make those systems more vulnerable to attacks.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>To determine if the organization requires attack surface reviews of newly developed systems, system components, and system services.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Attack surfaces of systems and system components are exposed areas that make those systems more vulnerable to attacks.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Attack surfaces include any accessible areas where weaknesses or deficiencies in the hardware, software, and firmware components provide opportunities for adversaries to exploit vulnerabilities.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Attack surface reviews ensure that developers analyze the design and implementation changes to systems and mitigate attack vectors generated as a result of the changes.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>The correction of identified flaws includes deprecation of unsafe functions.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization requires an attached surface review for all newly developed systems, system components, and system services that support the critical service/HVA environment.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization requires an attached surface review for some of the newly developed systems, system components, and system services.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>For all newly developed systems, system components, and system services there should be a documented attack surface review and associated results.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 <span>SA-11(6)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6220
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Managing the vulnerabilities identified during the attack surface reviews will reduce risk to organizations by giving attackers less opportunity to exploit weaknesses or deficiencies.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> To determine if the organization employs its risk management process to manage the closure of the vulnerabilities identified during the attack surface reviews.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Attack surface reduction is closely aligned with threat and vulnerability analyses and system architecture and design.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Attack surface reduction is a means of reducing risk to organizations by giving attackers less opportunity to exploit weaknesses or deficiencies (i.e., potential vulnerabilities) within systems, system components, and system services.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Attack surface reduction includes:</span></li>&#10;    <li>implementing the concept of layered defenses,</li>&#10;    <li>applying the principles of least privilege and least functionality,</li>&#10;    <li>applying secure software development practices,</li>&#10;    <li>deprecating unsafe functions,</li>&#10;    <li>reducing entry points available to unauthorized users,</li>&#10;    <li>reducing the amount of code that executes,</li>&#10;    <li>and eliminating application programming interfaces (APIs) that are vulnerable to attacks.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization employs its risk management process (or other similar process)</span> <span>to manage the closure of <strong>all&#160;</strong>vulnerabilities identified during the attack surface reviews of the critical service/HVA environment.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization employs its risk management process (or other similar process)</span> <span>to manage the closure of <strong>some</strong> vulnerabilities identified during the attack surface reviews of the critical service/HVA environment.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Documentation detailing the implementation of the risk management process and its application to managing the vulnerabilities identified during attack surface reviews including the results of the process. This may be presented in the form of a report or other tracking mechanism.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments:</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST SP 800-53r5 <span>SA-15(5)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6221
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p class="Body"><b>Importance:</b> Security review is performed as part of a change management process to ensure that any system modifications maintain the established system security requirements and posture.</p><p class="Body-LessSpaceAfter"><b>Question Intent:</b> To determine if the security design principle of secure evolvability is implemented by the organization.</p><p class="ListBulleted1CxSpFirst"></p><ul><li>Provide mechanisms and structure resources to enable the system to be maintained, modified, extended, or used in new ways without increasing security or mission risk.</li><li>Do not commit to a static architecture or an architecture that is difficult to change.</li><li>The principle of secure system modification states that system modification maintains system security with respect to the security requirements and risk tolerance of stakeholders.</li><li>The procedures for system modification ensure that if the system is to maintain its trustworthiness, the same rigor that was applied to its initial development is applied to any system changes.</li><li><font size="2" color="black" face="Symbol"><span><font size="1" face="Times New Roman"><span>&#160;&#160;</span></font></span></font>Because modifications can affect the ability of the system to maintain its secure state, a careful security analysis of the modification is needed prior to its implementation and deployment. This principle parallels the principle of secure evolvability.</li><li>The principle of secure evolvability states that a system is developed to facilitate the maintenance of its security properties when there are changes to the system&#8217;s structure, interfaces, interconnections (i.e., system architecture), functionality, or configuration (i.e., security policy enforcement).</li></ul><p></p><p class="Criteria"><b>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</b></p><p class="CriteriaListBullet"></p><ul><li>The organization&#8217;s documented system modification process includes the security design principle of secure evolvability for all components of the system.</li></ul><p></p><p class="Criteria"><b>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</b></p><p class="CriteriaListBullet"></p><ul><li>The organization&#8217;s system modification process includes the security design principle of secure evolvability for some components of the system</li></ul><p></p><p class="Heading4-nonum"><b>Possible Evidence</b></p><p class="ListBulleted1"></p><ul><li><font size="2" color="black" face="Symbol"><span><font size="1" face="Times New Roman"><span>&#160;</span></font></span></font>Documented system modification process detailing the requirement for including secure evolvability for all changes to the system.</li></ul><b></b><p></p><p class="Heading4-nonum"><b>Reference to standards/source assessments</b></p><p class="ListBulleted1"></p><ul><li><font size="2" color="black" face="Symbol"><span><font size="1" face="Times New Roman"><span>&#160;</span></font></span></font>NIST SP 800-53r5 SA-8(8), SA-8(31)</li></ul><p></p>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6222
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p class="Body"><b>Importance:</b> A policy that requires the security design principle of secure system modification helps ensure that any system modifications maintain the established system security requirements and posture.</p><p class="Body-LessSpaceAfter"><b>Question Intent:</b> To determine if an established system modification policy or process requires that proposed changes follow secure design principles of secure system modification, and which does not negatively impact the overall security posture of the system environment.</p><p class="Body-LessSpaceAfter"></p><ul><li><span>Provide mechanisms and structure resources to enable the system to be maintained, modified, extended, or used in new ways without increasing security or mission risk.</span></li><li><span>The principle of secure system modification states that system modification maintains system security with respect to the security requirements and risk tolerance of stakeholders.</span></li><li><span>The procedures for system modification ensure that if the system is to maintain its trustworthiness, the same rigor that was applied to its initial development is applied to any system changes.</span></li></ul><p></p><p class="Criteria"><b>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</b></p><p class="Criteria"></p><ul><li><span>The organization&#8217;s documented system modification policy requires that all proposed changes to the system follow the principles of secure system modification.</span></li></ul><p></p><p class="CriteriaListBullet"></p><p class="Criteria"><b>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</b></p><p class="Criteria"></p><ul><li><span>The organization&#8217;s system modification policy requires that all proposed changes to the system follow the principles of secure system modification, which may be applied in an ad hoc manner.</span></li></ul><p></p><p class="CriteriaListBullet"></p><p class="Heading4-nonum"><b>Possible Evidence</b></p><p class="Heading4-nonum"></p><ul><li><span>Documented system modification process detailing the requirement for including secure system modification for all changes to the system.</span></li></ul><p></p><p class="ListBulleted1"></p><p class="Heading4-nonum"><b>Reference to standards/source assessments</b></p><p class="Heading4-nonum"></p><ul><li><font size="2" face="Symbol"><span><font size="1" face="Times New Roman"><span>&#160;</span></font></span></font><span>NIST SP 800-53r5 </span><span>CM-3, SA-8(8), SA-8(31)</span></li></ul><p></p><p class="ListBulleted1"></p>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6223
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Performing system maintenance or reconfiguration increases the likelihood of a system outage that may disrupt mission essential functions.</p>&#10;&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the organization has identified and implemented the use of appropriate outage windows.&#160;</p><p><br></p>&#10;&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p><div><ul><li>The organization has identified appropriate times to perform system reconfiguration which will minimize negative impacts to the system and adhere to those maintenance windows.</li></ul></div><p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p><div><ul><li>The organization has identified appropriate times to perform system reconfiguration but does not fully adhere to them.&#160; &#160;</li></ul>&#10;&#10;</div>&#10;&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p><div><ul><li>Configuration Management Plan</li>&#10;&#10;&#160; &#160; </ul>&#10;&#10;</div>&#10;&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p><div><ul><li><span>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5:&#160;</span>IR-4(2)</li></ul>&#10;&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6224
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Staff that do not possess the necessary skills to perform configuration changes may cause extended outages or introduce errors into the system. Automated systems may mitigate this risk by providing consistency</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if there are staff members available to perform the required changes, or configure the available automated systems, to perform required changes.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has a staffing plan in place that includes a list of required skills necessary to fulfill the needs of each position performing system reconfiguration, to include, if applicable, maintenance of any automated systems.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Ad hoc configuration support without clearly defined skillsets.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Staffing plan and or automated system identified in a System Security Plan.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: AT-3</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6225
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Threat intelligence, or other external sources, may be employed to assist in performing reconfiguration based on current relevant threats to the system.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the organization is incorporating the latest industry relevant source data into its reconfiguration plan.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization utilizes at least one automatically updating threat intelligence source that is tailored to the target system(s).</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization utilizes threat intelligence data on an irregular schedule or without tailoring to the target system(s).</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Configuration Management Plan, System Security Plans</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CM-6(1), PM-16(1)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6226
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> IDS solutions are not static and need to be regularly updated to address current and relevant threats.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the system is utilizing a data source to inform IDS detection rulesets based on current and relevant information.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Threat intelligence feeds are used to inform IDS rulesets.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>IDS are in place but do not incorporate threat intelligence data.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>System Security Plans, Runbooks for IDS</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CM-6(1), PM-16(1)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6227
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> A compromised host may provide a vector for further system compromise.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the system uses endpoint protection via host isolation upon identification of system compromise.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The system has an endpoint detection and response solution that automatically isolates system components based current configuration and threat intelligence data.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The system has an endpoint detection and response solution that is capable of host isolation, but that capability does not automatically isolate system components, or it is only employed on a manual or &#160;ad hoc basis.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>System Security Plans</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SI-4(3), SC-7(20), IR-4(2)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6228
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> A compromised host may provide a vector for further system compromise.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the system used firewall or IDS host isolation upon identification of system compromise.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The system has a firewall solution that automatically isolates system components based current configuration and threat intelligence data.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The system has a firewall solution that does not automatically isolate systems upon threat detection.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Specific implementation details in a System Security Plan (SSP).</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SI-4(3), SC-7(20), IR-4(2)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6229
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font size="4" face="Arial">Does the organization have the capability to manage capacity, bandwidth, or other redundancy to limit negative impacts?</font><span></span></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Service or application outages may be caused by over utilization.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Write here what the question is trying to ascertain.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization employs techniques for balancing all critical application and service application resources.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has a mechanism in in place</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Specific implementation details in a System Security Plan (SSP).</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IR-4(2)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6230
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Service or application outages may be caused by over utilization. Load balancing across multiple systems reduces this risk.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Does the system have a load balancing solution to help reduce the risk of resource exhaustion? &#160;If the organization outsources critical application or service support to a service provider, then the question applies to the service provider.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization employs load balancers for all critical application and service application.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has a load balancing configuration that does not consider the criticality of applications or resources.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Specific implementation details in a System Security Plan (SSP)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SC-5(2)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6231
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Prioritization of events determine the application of resources. Application of resources influences outcomes.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> Determine what the SOC&#8217;s, if present, procedure for prioritizing incidents.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>There is an SOC with a clear and written incident response policy that includes prioritization guidance.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>There is generic guidance that informs an ad hoc decision concerning the prioritization of incident response activities.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Incident Response Plan, System Security Plans</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IR-6</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6232
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font size="4" face="Arial">Does the organization have the capability to deploy storage or compute resources dynamically?</font><span></span></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Static system resources introduce bottlenecks in terms of accessibility and capacity.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the system dynamically deploys storage or compute resources. Managing capacity ensures that sufficient capacity is available to counter flooding attacks. Managing capacity includes establishing selected usage priorities, quotas, partitioning, or load balancing.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization can deploy both storage and compute resources, as needed, for all system components without intervention.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization can provision storage and compute resources, but that capability requires direct human intervention.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>System Security Plans</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: AC-4(3), SC-5(2), CP-13</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6233
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Anomalous user or system account behavior can be an indicator of compromise. The ability to limit access to or from potentially compromises environments may aid in securing the overall system.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the system possesses the ability to automatically disable access. Organizations plan for the dynamic deactivation of system accounts by establishing trust relationships, business rules, and mechanisms with appropriate authorities to validate related authorizations and privileges.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The system has the capability to automatically disable accounts or isolate hosts based on parameterized rule sets.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The system has the capability to disable user accounts or host accessibility but does not do so automatically.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>System Security Plans</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: AC-2(8)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6234
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong>Importance:</strong> Anomalous login behavior such as out of hour logins, unreasonable times and distance between login attempts, or login duration may be indicators or attack or compromise.</p>&#10;<p><strong>Question Intent:&#160;</strong>Determine if the system is capable of assessing suspicious behavior and requiring additional authentication information. Organizations may employ specific techniques or mechanisms and establish protocols to assess suspicious behavior. Suspicious behavior may include accessing information that individuals do not typically access as part of their duties, roles, or responsibilities; accessing greater quantities of information than individuals would routinely access; or attempting to access information from suspicious network addresses. When pre-established conditions or triggers occur, organizations can require individuals to provide additional authentication information. Another potential use for adaptive authentication is to increase the strength of mechanism based on the number or types of records being accessed.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The system monitors for, identifies suspicious behavior and under specified conditions requires additional authentication information.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The system has the capability to identify anomalous login behavior but not to automatically require additional authentication information.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Possible Evidence</strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Specific implementation details in a System Security Plan (SSP).</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Reference to standards/source assessments</strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: AC-3(13), AC-7, IR-4(13), IA-10</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6235
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Artificial intelligence/machine learning solutions may provide more comprehensive information system and network protection from evolving attack vectors.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the system utilizes responsive AI and/or ML in its defensive capabilities.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization does utilize some form of AI/ML for system that is capable of automatically responding to identified threats.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The system utilizes AI/ML for system monitoring/logging, but that capability has no ability to respond to identified attacks or anomalous activity.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Runbooks or configuration files for network devices, specific implementation details in a System Security Plan (SSP).</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: RA-3(4)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6236
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font size="4" face="Arial">Has the organization defined its role in the supply chain and reviewed it for updates at least annually?</font><span></span></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Defining the organization&#8217;s role in the supply chain is important to then determine appropriate protections against supply chain threats to the system.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the organization has defined its role in the supply chain.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization has defined its role in the supply chain by documenting its supply chain dependencies, and</li>&#10;    <li>The organization conducts an annual review.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has defined its role in the supply chain but there is no periodic review.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>A document listing all supply chain dependencies for the given system. ISA/MOUs for third party interconnections. SLAs for third parties. Indications of periodic review. Supply Chain Risk Management Plan.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SR-1</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6237
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Communicating the organization&#8217;s role in the supply chain, and its supply chain dependencies, is important to ensure that supply chain resilience requirements can be met.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the organization has communicated its role in the supply chain to internal and external stakeholders.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization&#8217;s role in the supply chain and its supply chain resilience requirements have been communicated to all internal and external stakeholders.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization&#8217;s role in the supply chain is only communicated to a partial (between 30% and 70%) subset of stakeholders.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Supply Chain Risk Management Plan.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SI-5(1), CP-2, IR-4(10)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6238
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Identifying the organization&#8217;s place in critical infrastructure is important to then determine appropriate protection strategies for critical infrastructure.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the organization has identified its place in critical infrastructure.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has identified its place in critical infrastructure in appropriate documentation.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The place in critical infrastructure is identified but there is no periodic review.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>A critical infrastructure and key resources protection plan has been developed, documented, and is kept updated</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: PM-8</li>&#10;    <li>DHS Publication: &#8220;A Guide to Critical Infrastructure and Key Resources Protection at the State, Regional, Local, Tribal, and Territorial Level&#8221;</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6239
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Write here why we&#8217;re asking this question. Communicating the organization&#8217;s place in critical infrastructure is important to ensure that critical infrastructure planning and resilience requirements can be met.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the organization''s place in critical infrastructure been communicated to internal and external stakeholders.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Evidence that organization&#8217;s place in critical infrastructure has been communicated to internal and external stakeholders.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization&#8217;s place in critical infrastructure is only communicated to a partial (between 30% and 70%) subset of internal and external stakeholders.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Evidence that organization&#8217;s place in critical infrastructure has been communicated to internal and external stakeholders.&#160;</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: PM-8</li>&#10;    <li>DHS Publication: &#8220;A Guide to Critical Infrastructure and Key Resources Protection at the State, Regional, Local, Tribal, and Territorial Level&#8221;</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6240
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Identification of critical services would be a result of prioritization efforts.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the organization has identified its critical services or HVAs.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Critical Services</span></strong>: &#160; Services are activities the organization carries out in the performance of a duty or in the production of a product. Critical services are services on which the success of the organization&#8217;s mission depends.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>A list of critical services and HVAs is kept current (reviewed and updated at least annually).</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>A list of critical services or HVAs is available, but ignored, or out of date.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>A list of critical services, a list of HVAs</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>IMR: EH:G1.Q1</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: RA-9</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6241
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'Is the organization&#8217;s mission, vision, value, and purpose identified and communicated?', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Strategic objectives and mission, vision, values, and purpose form the basis for resilience activities. They provide essential and necessary guidance and direction for resilience activities.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the organization&#8217;s mission, vision, values, and purpose are identified and communicated.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has documentation which has been shared with stakeholders, that identifies the organization&#8217;s strategic objectives, mission, vision, values, and purpose.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Partial implementation would only include a subset of the desired elements, such as only objectives but no mission/vision, or only mission/vision, but no objectives.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Organizational strategic objectives; Organization mission, vision, values, and purpose statement.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>CRR: AM:G1.Q3</li>&#10;    <li>CERT RMM EF:SG1:SP1</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: RA-9, PM-11</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6242
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Prioritization of organizational objectives and activities will help prioritize the assets and services supporting these. The high-value services that support strategic objectives should be prioritized as the focus of resilience activities.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the organization prioritizes its mission, objectives, and activities.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has categorized its objectives and supporting activities into different priorities &#8211; or at least higher priority than other less essential objectives and activities.&#160;</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Only objectives or only activities but not both are prioritized.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Prioritized list of high-value services, list of prioritized objectives, list of prioritized activities.&#160;</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: RA-2(1), PM-11</li>&#10;    <li>CRR: AM:G1.Q4</li>&#10;    <li>CERT RMM EF:SG1.SP3</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6243
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> This question is asked to understand the prioritization criteria. Services should be prioritized based on potential impact, otherwise one could perform prioritization that is simply done based on tradition, politics, or other factors.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if services and facilities are prioritized based on analysis of potential impact.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization must have documented prioritization of facilities or services.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>A prioritization scheme exists, but there is no list of prioritized facilities or services.</li>&#10;    <li>All services and facilities have a business impact analysis, but there is no list of prioritized facilities or services.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Prioritized list of high-value organizational services, activities, and associated assets</li>&#10;    <li>Results of security risk assessment and business impact analyses</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>CRR: AM:G1.Q2</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: RA-2(1)</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6244
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Determine if the organization focuses organizational capabilities on its most critical services and processes.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the organization has an established prioritization process for services and HVAs and if it is actually used to good effect in focusing organizational capabilities.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Evidence from various relevant processes (incident handling and response, service continuity, vulnerability management, etc.) that critical services and HVAs are given due priority over other general services and assets.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Prioritization for critical services and HVAs is only done in one or two capabilities.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Evidence from various relevant processes (incident handling and response, service continuity, vulnerability management, etc.) that critical services and HVAs are considered and given due priority over other general (lower priority) services and assets.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>IMR: EH:G1.Q2</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: RA-9</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6245
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font face="Arial" size="4">Are the associations between assets and the critical service they support documented and updated as needed at least annually?</font><font face="Franklin Gothic Book, sans-serif"></font></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Documenting the relationship between assets and the critical services they support enables effective development, implementation, and management of resilience strategies supporting the organization&#8217;s mission.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the organization documents associations between assets and the critical services they support.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has a list of high-value services and associated assets which is current (updated at least annually)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>List of high-value services without associated assets, or less than 30% of services having associated assets identified.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>List of high-value services and associated assets</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>CRR: AM:G3.Q1</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: AC-16, CM-8, CP-2(8)</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6246
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Heading3-nonum"><font size="4" face="Arial"><font>Has the organization identified the data connections (data flows) between the critical service and other systems, including other critical services, to understand critical dependencies?</font><font>&#8239;</font></font><br></p><p class="Body"></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> To understand critical dependencies between the HVA/critical service and other systems.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if the organization has identified the data connections (data flows) between the HVA/critical service and other systems, including other HVAs, to gain an understanding of critical dependencies. &#160; The HVA/critical service may be cloud-based and still have critical dependencies on other systems and critical services, which should be understood. &#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Data flow diagram including narrative explanation of data flows and set of ISAs/MOUs for each interconnection with other systems</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Incomplete data flow diagram including narrative explanation of data flow) and set of ISAs/MOUs for each interconnection with other systems (provides coverage for at least 40% but less than 75% of data flows and interconnections).</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Data flow diagram including narrative explanation of data flow; ISA or MOU for interconnections with other systems</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>HVA: CM:CON.Q1</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-8, RA-9, PE-9, PE-11, PM-8</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6247
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font size="4" face="Arial">Is the prioritization of assets reviewed and validated?</font><font face="Franklin Gothic Book, sans-serif"></font></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> The asset list should be reviewed and validated periodically to ensure it remains valid/current.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if prioritization of assets is reviewed and validated periodically and how recent was the most recent review.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>There is a prioritized list of assets that has been reviewed and validated annually.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>There is a prioritized list of assets, but it does not seem to link facilities to priority services, or</li>&#10;    <li>There is a prioritized list of assets, but it has not been reviewed in over 12 months.&#160;</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>List of high-value assets with date (history) of reviews.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>CRR: AM:G7.Q2</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-2(8), CP-7(3), CP-8(1), PE-2, PE-17, PE-18, PE-23</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6248
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> This question is asked to assess whether the organization tracks its dependencies on external relationships that are critical to the high value service.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if dependencies on external relationships that are critical to critical services are identified</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>List of external dependencies and entities is documented and there is a documented process for updating this.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>List of external dependencies and entities is only partial, or only for some critical services.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>List of external dependencies and entities</li>&#10;    <li>Documented process for updating the list of external dependencies and entities.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>CRR: EDM:G1.Q1</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-8, RA-9, PE-9, PE-11, PM-8</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6249
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:&#160;</span></strong>Prioritization is important to ensure that resilience resources are directed where they best support the mission.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if external dependencies are prioritized. External dependencies can include IT infrastructure providers, software-as-a-service providers, utilities, or data or voice service providers, to name just a few.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Criteria for prioritizing external dependencies and prioritized list of external dependencies.&#160;</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Response:&#160;</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Having only partial list of external dependencies with no criteria for prioritization.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Criteria for prioritizing external dependencies and prioritized list of external dependencies.&#160;</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>CRR: EDM:G1.Q3</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-8(1), RA-9, PE-9, PE-11, PM-8</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6250
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'Are confidentiality, integrity, and availability requirements established for each service-related asset?', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> CIA requirements should be documented to ensure their resilience needs are planned for.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Whether confidentiality, integrity, and availability requirements are established for each service-related asset?</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>A list of confidentiality, integrity, and availability requirements is established for each critical service-related asset</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>A list of confidentiality, integrity, and availability requirements is established for only for a partial list (more than 40% but less than 75%) of critical service-related assets</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>List of confidentiality, integrity, and availability requirements established for each critical service-related asset</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>CRR: AM:G3.Q2-PITF</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: PL-8, CP-9</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6251
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Defined availability requirements are an important part of a service continuity plan which help determine the resilience requirements.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if availability requirements, such as MTD, RTO and RPO been established for the HVA and whether they were determined by a reasonable process.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Availability requirements are defined and established via a reasonable process to meet organizational mission needs.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Availability requirements are defined but the process cannot be determined or does not seem reasonable. Only one or two availability requirements is defined.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>List of availability requirements and an explanation of how they were determined. Business Impact Assessment including availability requirements.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>HVA: SC:SB.Q5</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-6(2)</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6252
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Critical services may have external dependencies with associated resilience requirements.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Determine if resilience requirements of the critical service been established that apply specifically to each external dependency</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Documented resilience requirements for each external dependency and associated service level agreements</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Having partial (over 40% but less than 75%) SLAs and resilience requirements&#160;</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Documented resilience requirements for each external dependency, Service level agreements</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>CRR: EDM:G3.Q1</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SA-9, SR-3, SR-6</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6253
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong>Importance:</strong> Frequent changes in the cybersecurity landscape require regular updates in resilience requirements if an organization is going to maintain its resilience posture.</p>&#10;<p><strong>Question Intent:&#160;</strong>To determine if the organization has a process to periodically review and update resilience requirements for infrastructure providers that support the critical service.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization&#8217;s dependence on infrastructure providers may change in scope and importance based on business and service considerations, or on factors outside the acquirer&#8217;s control. Therefore, it is important that the acquirer has a process to periodically review and update resilience requirements for infrastructure providers.</li>&#10;    <li>Periodically means that the acquirer has a documented time interval for the activity.</li>&#10;    <li>Having an established process means that:</li>&#10;    <li>There are specific steps or activities that acquirer staff must complete.</li>&#10;    <li>The process is supported by appropriate documentation. For example, there may be a documented schedule of meetings to identify requirements.</li>&#10;    <li>The acquirer&#8217;s staff is aware that the process exists and that they are expected to follow it.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Responsibility for monitoring the performance of each infrastructure provider that supports the critical service has been assigned.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Responsibility for monitoring the performance of some infrastructure providers has been assigned, or the practice appears otherwise incomplete.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Possible Evidence</strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Internal policy or command media documenting activity and period</li>&#10;    <li>Notes from recurring meetings</li>&#10;    <li>Internal correspondence</li>&#10;    <li>Staff job descriptions assigning responsibility</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Reference to standards/source assessments</strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>EDM: RMG:G6.Q1</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-2, CP-2(7), SR-1, SR-3, SR-7</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6254
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong>Importance:</strong> Managing capacity ensures that sufficient capacity is available to counter flooding attacks. Managing capacity includes establishing selected usage priorities, quotas, partitioning, or load balancing.</p>&#10;<p><strong>Question Intent:&#160;</strong>Determine if the organization conducts capacity management and planning. Specifically, does the organization consider the potential impact of flooding attacks, and has it deployed countermeasures to prevent or recover from these types of attacks?</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Definition of any key words with examples</li>&#10;    <li>Flooding attack</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>(1) The organization has a documented process for conducting capacity management and planning. (2) The organization has conducted an analysis to identify and characterize the types of flooding attacks that might occur. (3) The organization has deployed countermeasures to prevent or recover from these types of attacks.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization performs 1 or 2 of items 1), 2), or 3) in &#8220;Criteria for Full Implementation Response.&#8221;</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Possible Evidence</strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Capacity management and planning document (policy or procedure), SC-5(2) control implementation description</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Reference to standards/source assessments</strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SC-5(2)</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6255
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong><span>&#160;The use of capacity metrics, to identify trends, enables the organization to evaluate the&#160;</span>effectiveness of its capacity management plan.</p>&#10;<p><strong>Question Intent:&#160;</strong>Does the organization collect capacity measurements and identify trends? Are these trends used to validate capacity management activities, and as applicable, make changes to the capacity management plans?</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Definition of any key words with examples</li>&#10;    <li>Measurement:</li>&#10;    <li>Metric: a standard for measuring or evaluating something</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>(1) The organization collects capacity measurements in accordance with a documented Information Technology or cybersecurity metrics plan or program. (2) The organization conducts trend analysis to evaluate the effectiveness of its capacity management plan.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization collects capacity measurements but does not have a documented Information Technology or cybersecurity metrics plan or program.</li>&#10;    <li>The organization collects capacity measurements in accordance with a documented Information Technology or cybersecurity metrics plan or program but does utilize the measurements to identify trends.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Possible Evidence</strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Information Security of cybersecurity metrics plan or program document, trend charts or graphs</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Reference to standards/source assessments</strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IR-3(3)</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6256
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong>Importance:</strong> Threat intelligence is a key component of a cybersecurity program. The identification and characterization of the threat enables cyber defenders to plan and execute defensive operations at the right time, with the right resources.</p>&#10;<p><strong>Question Intent:&#160;</strong>Does the organization have a dedicated threat intelligence capability? What products does it produce and who consumes the products?</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Definition of any key words with examples</li>&#10;    <li>Indicator of Compromise</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization has personnel dedicated to threat intelligence analysis and threat intelligence production/dissemination. Threat intelligence informs the planning and execution of cybersecurity operations.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization has personnel that perform threat intelligence functions as an additional duty or on a part-time basis. Threat intelligence is disconnected from operational planning and execution.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Possible Evidence</strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Threat intelligence procedures, concepts of operations, list of threat intelligence sources, examples of threat intelligence products produced by the threat intelligence element.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Reference to standards/source assessments</strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: PM-16&#160;</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6257
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizations conduct threat hunting to search for indicators of compromise and detect, track, and disrupt threats that evade existing controls.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> Does the organization conduct threat hunting? If yes, who is responsible for conducting the activity and at what frequency?</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Definition of any key words with examples</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Threat hunting</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization conducts threat hunting activities in accordance with a documented threat hunting strategy, policy, or procedure at a frequency commensurate with the sensitivity and/or criticality of the service/system. (This content could be included in another strategy, policy, or procedure.)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization conducts threat hunting, but the activity is not documented or conducted at a frequency commensurate with the sensitivity and/or criticality of the service/system.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Document that defines threat hunting activities, to include the nature and frequency of the activities.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: RA-10</li>&#10;    <li><span>NIST 800-172: 3.11.2e</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6258
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:&#160;</span></strong>The organization&#8217;s ability to maintain a single, identical display of information facilitates the planning and execution of operational and security activities.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Does the organization maintain a mission-wide or organization-wide operational picture or dashboard that displays operational and security event or incidents? Does this &#8220;Common Operational Picture&#8221; support risk management and decision-making?</p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Definition of any key words with examples</span></li></ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Common Operational Picture (COP</span></strong>): A single, identical display of relevant information shared by more than one [organizational unit] that facilitates collaborative planning and assists all echelons to achieve situational awareness.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization maintains a mission-wide or organization-wide operational picture or dashboard that is monitored by dedicated personnel.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization maintains multiple operational pictures or dashboards. Collectively, the operational pictures or dashboard provide mission-wide or enterprise-wide coverage.</li>&#10;    <li>The organization maintains a mission-wide operational picture or dashboard, but it is not monitored by dedicated personnel.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Screenshots of the organization-wide operational picture or dashboard</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IR-4(14)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6259
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font size="4" face="Arial">Does the organization conduct an impact-level prioritization of organizational systems to obtain additional granularity on system impact levels?</font><span></span></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Considering the impact of IT Systems from a top-down approach, and evaluating them as a whole, sometimes will reveal that the security categorizations of individual devices are inaccurate when they are a component of a larger organizational system.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>to determine if the organization conducts impact-level prioritization of organizational systems to obtain additional granularity on individual system impact levels.</p>&#10;<p><span>The impact level of an individual system can raise or lower the impact level prioritization of an organizational system. Just as an individual systems location within an organization system can raise its own impact level, therefore, both organizational systems and individual information systems should be evaluated keeping the other in mind.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization conducts impact-level prioritizations of all organizational systems for the purpose of obtaining additional granularity on system impact levels.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization conducts impact-level prioritizations of some organizational systems for the purpose of obtaining additional granularity on system impact levels.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Documentation demonstrating impact levels of organizational systems.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IA-2(6)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6260
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font face="Arial" size="4">Does the organization require individuals accessing the system to employ organization-defined supplemental authentication techniques or mechanisms under specific organization-defined circumstances or situations?</font><font face="Franklin Gothic Book, sans-serif"></font></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong>Importance:&#160;</strong>Due to impact-level prioritization, some information systems within an organization may require additional security measures to protect them. Therefore, these systems should also employ supplemental authentication techniques or mechanisms where appropriate.</p>&#10;<p><strong>Question Intent:</strong> to determine if the organization requires supplemental authentication techniques or mechanisms when accessing information systems under specific organization-defined circumstances or situations</p>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization defines circumstances or conditions when supplemental authentication techniques or mechanisms are required to access information systems, and such security controls are implemented.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><em>&#160;</em>The organization requires additional authentication techniques or mechanisms to access certain information systems, however the organization does not define the circumstances or conditions that warrant these additional protections.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)&#160;</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Possible Evidence</strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Standard operating procedures regarding authentication processes, screenshots from a user&#8217;s point-of-view demonstrating a requirement to complete multiple distinct authentication challenges while establishing a session, screenshots from an administrator&#8217;s point of view showing that multi-factor authentication is enabled.&#160;</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Reference to standards/source assessments</strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SI-4(2), SC-7(12)</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6261
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><span><font face="Arial" size="4">Are multiple, distinct authentication challenges over the course of a session employed to confirm identity?</font></span><font face="Franklin Gothic Book, sans-serif"></font></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Multifactor authentication that employs multiple authentication mechanisms can prevent against attacks that leverage legitimate user credentials. By having multiple distinct authentication challenges that incorporate passphrases, biometrics, physical tokens, or SMS passcodes, organizations can make it significantly more difficult for adversaries to access user accounts.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> This question seeks to discover what authentication challenges are employed over the course of a user session and determine whether multifactor authentication is in use.</p>&#10;<p><span>Multifactor authentication uses two or more different factors to achieve authentication. Factors include something you know (e.g., PIN, password), something you have (e.g., cryptographic identification device, token), or something you are (e.g., biometric).</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization demonstrates that a minimum of two distinct authentication challenges are employed when initiating a user session.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization uses less than two authentication challenges or cannot provide input regarding specific details of the implementation.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Standard operating procedures regarding authentication processes, screenshots from a user&#8217;s point-of-view demonstrating a requirement to complete multiple distinct authentication challenges while establishing a session, screenshots from an administrator&#8217;s point of view showing that multi-factor authentication is enabled.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: RA-2</li>&#10;    <li><span>NIST 800-160, Rev. 1</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6262
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font face="Arial" size="4">Are both network and host-based intrusion detection employed for the protection of the HVA/critical service?</font><font face="Franklin Gothic Book, sans-serif"></font></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Network and host-based intrusion detection systems should be employed concurrently as they can detect different activity.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> This question will determine if the organization employs both network and host-based intrusion detection solutions.</p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Host-based intrusion detection systems monitor the activity of a single host for anomalous and suspicious behavior.</li>&#10;    <li>Network-based intrusion detection systems monitor network traffic for abnormal and suspicious network activity.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization employs both network and host-based intrusion detection solutions for the protection of critical services infrastructure and high value assets.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization employs a network-based or host-based intrusion detection solution. However, they do not utilize both.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Software inventory for the organization showing licenses for host-based and network-based IDS solutions, Device configurations.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: RA-2(1)</li>&#10;    <li><span>NIST 800-160, Rev. 1</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6263
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font face="Arial" size="4">Does the organization implement controls that monitor physical access to the system in addition to the physical access monitoring of facilities (where there is a concentration of system components, including server rooms, media storage areas, and communications centers)?</font><font face="Franklin Gothic Book, sans-serif"></font></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Monitoring physical access to systems provides additional monitoring for those areas within facilities where there is a concentration of system components, including server rooms, media storage areas, and communications centers.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization implements physical access controls to organizational systems in addition to the physical access monitoring of facilities.</p>&#10;<p><span>Physical access monitoring can be coordinated with intrusion detection systems and system monitoring capabilities to provide comprehensive and integrated threat coverage for the organization.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization implements controls that monitor physical access on all organizational systems.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization implements controls that monitor physical access on some organizational systems.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Configuration baselines showing that physical access controls are configured.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: PE-6(4)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6264
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Title]=N'Deleted', [Question_Text]=N'DELETED QUESTION', [Supplemental_Info]=N'' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6265
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'Does the organization coordinate cybersecurity activities across system, mission, and organizational levels?', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> The implementation of an organization&#8217;s cybersecurity strategy will vary depending on the business units responsible for its execution, therefore it is useful to consider how it is operationalized in different contexts across the organization.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question is seeking to learn more about how the organization coordinates cybersecurity activities across systems, missions, and organization levels.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The respondent is confident in their response, demonstrates clear knowledge of cybersecurity activities across the organization, and provides an example of how activities are implemented at each level.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The respondent is timid in their answer; However, they provide a brief response as to how cybersecurity activities are embedded in the organization&#8217;s business practices. More information could be provided on specific implementation with regards to the system, mission, and organization levels.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Organizational cybersecurity or information security strategy.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IA-1, PM-1, CP-4(1)</li>&#10;    <li><span>NIST 800-160, Rev. 1</span><span>&#160;</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6266
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Privileged account recertification should occur periodically within an organization to verify that privileges allocated to users are appropriate given their job duties and role.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization periodically reviews the privileges assigned to users to validate the need for such privileges and if privileges are removed or reassigned, when necessary, to correctly reflect organizational mission and business needs.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization periodically reviews the privileges assigned to users to validate the need for such privileges and when necessary, privileges are removed or reassigned to correctly reflect organizational mission and business needs.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization periodically reviews the privileges assigned to users to validate the need for such privileges. However, privileges are not consistently removed or reassigned to correctly reflect organizational mission and business needs.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Correspondence regarding the privileged account review and recertification process.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: AC-6(7)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6267
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Periodic recertification of privileged accounts is an important task to ensure that users are allocated privileges commensurate with their job duties and to ensure that the principle of least privilege is implemented at the system level.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question ascertains if the organization uses privilege analysis tools to support an ongoing review of whether user privileges are assigned consistently.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization utilizes privilege analysis tools that can support a continuous review of user privileges and how they are assigned across the organization.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization uses privilege analysis tools to support the review of user account privileges. However, the tools might not have capabilities to discern whether user privileges are assigned consistently across the organization.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Account management standard operating procedures, policy for user account provisioning.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-2(1)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6268
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> incident response plans, business continuity plans, disaster recovery plans, and contingency plans are all related, therefore their development should be coordinated with each other.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>if the organization coordinates contingency plan development with organizational elements responsible for related plans.</p>&#10;<p><span>Organizational elements responsible for related plans may include</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Cloud service providers</li>&#10;    <li>Incident response teams</li>&#10;    <li>Business continuity teams</li>&#10;    <li>Hot/warm/cold site providers</li>&#10;    <li>IT administrators responsible for backup management solutions</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization coordinates the development of contingency plan with all organizational elements responsible for related plans.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization coordinates the development of contingency plan with some organizational elements responsible for related plans.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Attestation from applicable personnel that multiple organizational elements are involved in the development of contingency plans, incident response plans, business continuity plans, and disaster recovery plans.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: AC-6(7)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6269
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Business continuity planning is critical to minimize losses.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization has a business continuity plan in place to provide the continuance of essential mission and business functions with minimal or no loss of operational continuity.</p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Business continuity planning requires organizations to perform business process analyses (BPAs), business impact analyses (BIAs), and risk assessments. These need to be performed to identify essential mission and business functions that require minimal or no loss of operation, so they can then be prioritized when planning for business continuity capabilities.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has a fully documented and developed business continuity function that provides for the continuance of essential mission and business functions with minimal or no loss of operational continuity.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization has a partially documented and developed business continuity function that provides for the continuance of essential mission and business functions with minimal or no loss of operational continuity.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Business continuity plan,<span>&#160;business process analyses (BPAs), business impact analyses (BIAs), risk assessments</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-2(5)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6270
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Critical services in the organization should be uniquely considered and have their own continuity procedures.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question seeks to ascertain whether the organizations service continuity plan is capable of sustaining continuity until full system restoration at primary processing and/or storage sites.</p>&#10;<p><span>Service continuity can be maintained using hot sites, warm sites, cold sites, alternate organizational facilities, cloud service providers, etc.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization&#8217;s service continuity plan is capable of sustaining continuity for all identified critical services until full system restoration at primary processing and storage sites</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organizations service continuity plan is capable of sustaining continuity for some identified critical services until full system restoration at primary processing and storage sites</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Service continuity plan, business continuity plan</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-2(5)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6271
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Certain incidents can cause significant amounts of destruction or disruption to business functions. Therefore, organizations should identify these incidents and document them in an incident management plan.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>If the incident management plan includes classes of incidents that require specific responses to ensure the continuation of mission-critical business functions.</p>&#10;<p><span>Classes of incidents include malfunctions due to design or implementation errors and omissions, targeted malicious attacks, and untargeted malicious attacks. Incident response actions include orderly system degradation, system shutdown, fall back to manual mode or activation of alternative technology whereby the system operates differently, employing deceptive measures, alternate information flows, or operating in a mode that is reserved for when systems are under attack.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization fully documents sub-classes of incidents and actions to take in response to such incidents to ensure continuation of organizational missions and business functions.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization partially documents sub-classes of incidents and actions to take in response to such incidents to ensure continuation of organizational missions and business functions.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Sub-classes of incidents and their corresponding actions as defined in the organizational incident management plan.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IR-4(3)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6272
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> If an organization experiences an incident due to a vulnerability that affects other organizations involved in the supply chain, there are specific reporting channels and processes the organization should follow to ensure responsible disclosure of the vulnerability.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization coordinates its incident handling activities that involve supply chain events with other organizations involved in the supply chain</p>&#10;<p><span>Organizations involved in supply chain activities include product developers, system integrators, manufacturers, packagers, assemblers, distributors, vendors, and resellers. Supply chain incidents can occur anywhere through or to the supply chain and include compromises or breaches that involve primary or sub-tier providers, information technology products, system components, development processes or personnel, and distribution processes or warehousing facilities. Organizations consider including processes for protecting and sharing incident information in information exchange agreements and their obligations for reporting incidents to government oversight bodies (e.g., Federal Acquisition Security Council).</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization coordinates all incident handling activities involving supply chain events with other organizations involved in the supply chain.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization coordinates some incident handling activities involving supply chain events with other organizations involved in the supply chain.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Supply chain risk management plan, communications management plan</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IR-4(10)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6273
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> If an organization does not have an on-call incident response capabilities, they may consider keeping an incident response retainer to comply with relevant regulations and laws.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines whether the organization has an incident response team that can be deployed to any location identified by the organization within specified time periods</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has an integrated incident response team&#8212;or equivalent supplied services--that can be deployed to any location identified by the organization within specified time periods.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization has an integrated incident response team&#8212;or equivalent supplied services--that can be deployed to any location identified by the organization, however there is not a guarantee they can be deployed within specified time periods.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Incident response plan, incident management plan, contract with incident response service provider for a retainer</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IR-4(11)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6274
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> If an organization does not have an on-call incident response capabilities, they may consider keeping an incident response retainer to comply with relevant regulations and laws.</p>&#10;&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines whether the organization has an incident response team that can be deployed to any location identified by the organization within specified time periods</p>&#10;&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong><span>&#160;&#160;</span></p><div><ul><li>The organization has an integrated incident response team&#8212;or equivalent supplied services--that can be deployed to any location identified by the organization within specified time periods.</li></ul>&#10;&#10;</div>&#10;&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p><ul><li>The organization has an integrated incident response team&#8212;or equivalent supplied services--that can be deployed to any location identified by the organization, however there is not a guarantee they can be deployed within specified time periods.</li><li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;&#10;</ul>&#10;&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p><div><ul><li>Incident response plan, incident management plan, contract with incident response service provider for a retainer</li></ul></div><p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p><div><ul><li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IR-4(11)</li>&#10;&#10;&#160; &#160; </ul>&#10;&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6275
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font face="Arial" size="4">Does the organization implement security functions as a layered structure minimizing interactions between layers of the design and avoiding any dependence by lower layers on the functionality or correctness of higher layers?&#160;</font><b></b></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong>Importance:</strong> Layered security is a core concept of defense-in-depth.</p>&#10;<p>SC-3: &#160;Security functions may be isolated by boundaries to minimize interactions between layers of design. The isolation boundary controls access to and protects the integrity of the hardware, software, and firmware that perform system security functions. Systems implement code separation in many ways, such as through the provision of security kernels via processor rings or processor modes. For non-kernel code, security function isolation is often achieved through file system protections that protect the code on disk and address space protections that protect executing code. Systems can restrict access to security functions using access control mechanisms and by implementing least privilege capabilities.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong>Question Intent:&#160;</strong>This question seeks to determine if the organization designs its security functions with layered security in mind.</p>&#10;<p>Security functions should be isolated from non-security functions by means of an isolation boundary implemented within a system via partitions and domains</p>&#10;<p>The isolation boundary controls access to and protects the integrity of the hardware, software, and firmware that perform system security functions.</p>&#10;<p>The implementation of layered structures with minimized interactions among security functions and non-looping layers (i.e., lower-layer functions do not depend on higher-layer functions) enables the isolation of security functions and the management of complexity.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization prioritizes layered security when implementing new security functions and is cognizant to ensure that any interactions and dependencies between the layered of the design are kept to an absolute minimum, with security functions existing independently of each other</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization prioritizes layered security when implementing new security functions and tries to limit interactions and dependencies between layers of the design. However, there are security functions that are provided at the same layer with no redundant functions and/or depend on the functioning of another.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Possible Evidence</strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Security architecture diagram</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong>Reference to standards/source assessments</strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SC-3(5)</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6276
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font face="Arial" size="4">Does the organization synchronize duplicate systems or system components?</font><font face="Franklin Gothic Book, sans-serif"></font></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> If the organization has duplicate systems for the purpose of service continuity, such systems should be synchronized to ensure a smooth transition to the secondary site if required.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>The question is seeking to determine if the organization synchronizes duplicate systems and/or system components.</p>&#10;<p><span>Systems and/or system components should be duplicated in distributed locations. The synchronization of duplicated and redundant services and data helps to ensure that information contained in the distributed locations can be used in the mission or business functions of organizations, as needed.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization synchronizes all duplicate systems or system components.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization synchronizes some duplicate systems or system components.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Configuration of systems/system components at secondary sites.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SC-36(2)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6277
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Title]=N'deleted', [Question_Text]=N'DELETED QUESTION', [Supplemental_Info]=N'' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6278
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Social engineering exploits human trust to obtain access to organizational assets or resources that wouldn&#8217;t otherwise be granted. Many attacks use social engineering techniques such as phishing or vishing to obtain initial entry into systems, therefore it is crucial to train organizational personnel to recognize when social engineering attempts are taking place.</p>&#10;<p><span>Practical exercises include no-notice social engineering attempts to collect information, gain unauthorized access, or simulate the adverse impact of opening malicious email attachments or invoking, via spear phishing attacks, malicious web links.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent</span></strong>: This question ascertains if the organization uses practical exercises to train employees on how to recognize social engineering attempts as they occur.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>All organizational personnel receive practical exercises to help them to recognize social engineering attempts.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><em><span>&#160;</span></em>Some organizational personnel receive practical exercises to help them to recognize social engineering attempts.</li>&#10;    <li>Or, all organizational personnel receive training in how to recognize social engineering attempts however the training does not include practical exercises.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Curriculum from organizational security training that covers social engineering and provides a practical interactive component.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: AT-2(1)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6279
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> As real-world attacks don&#8217;t follow an organization defined schedule, penetration testing activities should occur within a given frequency as well as at randomized times.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> This question determines whether the organization<strong><span>&#160;</span></strong>conducts penetration testing on organization-defined systems or system components in accordance with an organization defined frequency or schedule.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The accordance conducts penetration testing on organization-defined systems or system components in accordance with the organization-defined frequency.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The accordance conducts penetration testing on organization-defined systems or system components however it isn&#8217;t performed in accordance with an organization-defined frequency.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)&#160;</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Penetration testing reports</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CA-8</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6280
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><span><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong><span>&#160;Using an independent team or external firm specializing in penetration tests can provide&#160;</span>additional perspectives to the engagement and create a more effective adversary emulation if the organization is seeking to mimic an attack from a competent, sophisticated adversary--I.e., an attack advanced persistent threat group.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question discerns what party or entity is responsible for the performance of penetration testing against organizational systems or system components.</p>&#10;<p><span>Having penetration tests being performed by an independent testing agent has their limitations in the reporting as you&#8217;re limited to the toolkit and skillset of a single penetration tester, however this may be more cost effective depending on the size and scope of the penetration testing engagement desired.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Additional factors such as whether the penetration tester is an employee of the organization can also determine the kind of testing exercise able to be performed, while organizational personnel may be capable of performing a &#8220;white box&#8221; pen test, they would not fully be able to perform a &#8220;black box&#8221; test due to their familiarity and knowledge of the organization.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>This may be a justification for external penetration testing services, to get an honest look at what is visible to outsiders.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>If seeking to emulate an insider threat, there are benefits to using penetration testers with knowledge of the organization.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization employs an independent penetration testing agent or teams to perform penetration testing on organizational systems or system components.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization employs an independent penetration testing agent or teams to perform penetration testing on some organizational systems or system components, but not all.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Copy of a penetration testing report / write up authored by an independent penetration testing agent or team.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CA-8(1)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6281
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font face="Arial" size="4">Does the organization disrupt and adversely affect the system or system component to validate the effectiveness of protections?</font><font face="Franklin Gothic Book, sans-serif"></font></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Contingency plans should be tested to ensure that protections are implemented properly.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question seeks to determine if the organization tests systems using planned disruptions that have an adverse effect on system performance to validate that the protections in place are effective.</p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Example: Stress testing can be used to test the efficacy of load balancing solutions.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>the organization tests all relevant systems using planned disruptions that have an adverse effect on system performance to validate that the protections in place are effective.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>the organization tests some systems using planned disruptions that have an adverse effect on system performance to validate that the protections in place are effective.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Reports or documentation created as a result of contingency plan tests.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CA-8(2), CP-4(5)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6282
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font face="Arial" size="4">Does the organization conduct red-team exercises to simulate attempts by adversaries in real-world conditions to compromise organizational systems in accordance with applicable rules of engagement?</font><font face="Franklin Gothic Book, sans-serif"></font></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Standard red-team exercises do not always leverage the most useful threat modeling techniques. Crafting an adversary emulation that is informed by organizational threat intelligence and leverages adversary tactics, techniques, and procedures the organization has experienced previously can provide real-world conditions for use in penetration testing engagements.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent</span></strong>: This question determines if the organization uses red-team exercises that simulate attempts by adversaries in real-world conditions to compromise organizational systems.</p>&#10;<p><span>Rules of engagement define the vectors, tactics, tools, and systems that are in-scope for the red-team exercise.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization periodically conducts red-team exercises that simulate attempts by adversaries in real-world conditions to compromise organizational systems. These exercises abide by applicable rules of engagement.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization periodically conducts red-team exercises to simulate the compromise of organizational systems. However, these exercises do not have realistic rules of engagement defined which can affect the value of exercise results and make the simulated attacks stray too far from what the organization is likely to see in a real-world scenario.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>An after-action report or lessons learned report from a red-team exercise conducted against the organization, rules of engagement used in red-team exercises.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CA-8(3)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6283
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font face="Arial" size="4">Does the organization test backup information with certain frequency to verify media reliability and information integrity?</font><font face="Franklin Gothic Book, sans-serif"></font></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Even if a back-up of a critical system is performed, the back-ups must be tested to ensure that the back-ups are not corrupted, and that they would be useful in the instance those back-ups were operationally required.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization has a defined frequency in which they test backup information to verify media reliability and information integrity.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>the organization regularly tests all backup information to verify media reliability and information integrity in accordance with the organization-defined frequency.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>the organization regularly tests some backup information to verify media reliability and information integrity in accordance with the organization-defined frequency.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Ticketing or reports demonstrating that backup media has been tested in accordance with the<span>&#160;defined frequency.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-4(5)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6284
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body-LessSpaceAfter"><font color="black" size="4" face="Arial">Does the organization require the developer of the system, system component, or system service to perform penetration testing:</font></p><p class="ListNumbered2CxSpFirst"><font size="4" face="Arial"><font color="black"><span>a.<span>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </span></span></font>at a given level of rigor (breadth and depth) and</font></p><p class="ListNumbered2CxSpLast"><font size="4" face="Arial"><font color="black"><span>b.<span>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </span></span></font>under organization-defined constraints?</font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> The quality of penetration testing engagements can vary; therefore, organizations should specify the level of rigor and scope of such tests to accurately model the types of attacks they are likely to face as an organization.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question seeks to determine if the organization holds penetration testing exercises to quality standards such as rigor and organization-defined constraints.</p>&#10;<p><span>Penetration tests should incorporate adversary emulation techniques, use pre-determined levels of rigor, and consider any organization-defined constraints that may limit the scope of the testing</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization requires the developers of systems, system components, or system services to perform penetration testing and specifies a given level of rigor (breadth and depth) as well as any additional organization-defined constraints that the penetration test must follow.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization requires the developers of systems, system components, or system services to perform penetration testing, however the organization does not specify a given level of rigor (breadth and depth) or organization-defined constraints for the penetration testing.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)&#160;</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Rules of engagement for a penetration test performed against the system, system component, or system service that includes description of the level of rigor used, as well as the constraints the penetration testers had to work under.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-9(1)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6285
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'<p class="Body"><font color="black"><font face="Arial" size="4">Does the organization employ a penetration testing process that includes attempts to bypass or circumvent controls associated with physical access points to the facility?</font><font face="Franklin Gothic Book, sans-serif"></font></font></p>', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Threat actors can gain access to physical organizational facilities through means of social engineering, lock picking, hardware hacking, and other adversarial techniques. Therefore, penetration tests should incorporate testing of physical facilities and access points as well.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent</span></strong>: This question ascertains whether the organization conducts physical penetration testing exercises that circumvent controls associated with physical access points to the facility.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>the organization has conducted penetration testing that includes attempts to bypass or circumvent controls associated with physical access points to organizational facilities.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>the organization has not incorporated physical facility access into the scope of its penetration testing engagements, however there are plans in place to conduct such an engagement in the future.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Penetration test report or write up that includes findings pertaining to the physical security of organizational facilities.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SA-11(5)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6286
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'Does the organization:<br/>(a) Prevent the exfiltration of information; and<br/>(b) Conduct exfiltration tests?', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> While organizational data flows can be monitored, and data loss prevention solutions can help stop the unauthorized exfiltration of information, these mechanisms should be tested to ensure that they function properly.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization prevents the exfiltration of information and conducts tests of the data exfiltration prevention mechanisms in place.</p>&#10;<p><span>Techniques used to prevent the exfiltration of information from systems may be implemented at internal endpoints, external boundaries, and across managed interfaces and include adherence to protocol formats, monitoring for beaconing activity from systems, disconnecting external network interfaces except when explicitly needed, employing traffic profile analysis to detect deviations from the volume and types of traffic expected, call backs to command and control centers, conducting penetration testing, monitoring for steganography, disassembling and reassembling packet headers, and using data loss and data leakage prevention tools.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has security controls and solutions implemented to prevent the exfiltration of information and they undergo testing to ensure proper functionality.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization has security controls and solutions implemented to prevent the exfiltration of information however they are not tested to ensure proper functionality.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation).</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Report of a data exfiltration test conducted against anti-exfiltration security countermeasures.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SC-7(10)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6287
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Alternate telecommunications services are used to minimize common mode failures, particularly threat events that exploit common vulnerabilities.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if alternate telecommunications services from providers that are separated from primary service providers are in use to reduce susceptibility to the same threats and enhance the resilience of the mission critical business service.</p>&#10;<p><span>Threats that affect telecommunications services are defined in organizational assessments of risk and include natural disasters, structural failures, cyber or physical attacks, and errors of omission or commission.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Organizations can reduce common susceptibilities by minimizing shared infrastructure among telecommunications service providers and achieving sufficient geographic separation between services.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Organizations may consider using a single service provider in situations where the service provider can provide alternate telecommunications services that meet the separation needs addressed in the risk assessment and meet the critical service requirements.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Obtaining alternate telecommunications services can also reduce the likelihood of sharing a single point of failure with primary telecommunications services.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization has identified all primary telecommunication services used to support the critical business service and has obtained an alternate service for each of the identified primary communication services.</li>&#10;    <li>And, each alternate service is separated from the associated primary telecommunication service.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization has obtained an alternate service for some of the identified primary telecommunication services.</li>&#10;    <li>Or, only some of the alternate telecommunication services are separated from the associated primary telecommunication service.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible evidence:</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Listing of all primary and alternate telecommunications providers and associated documentation showing service separation.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-8(3)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6288
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Employing alternate communication protocols can minimize common mode failures, particularly threat events that exploit common vulnerabilities and can be incorporated as part of an overall resilience strategy.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if an organization employs alternative communications protocols in support of maintaining continuity of operations to enhance the resilience of the mission critical business service.</p>&#10;<p><span>Use multiple sets of technical standards, different technologies, and different architectural patterns to minimize common mode failures, particularly threat events that exploit common vulnerabilities.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Contingency plans and the contingency training or testing associated with those plans incorporate an alternate communications protocol capability as part of establishing resilience in organizational systems.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Switching communications protocols may affect software applications and operational aspects of systems. Organizations should assess the potential side effects of introducing alternate communications protocols prior to implementation.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has developed and documented the capability to employ organization-defined alternative communication protocols for maintaining continuity of operations.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization is in the process of developing and documenting the capability to employ organization-defined alternative communication protocols</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible evidence:</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Architectural documentation</li>&#10;    <li>Contingency plans documenting the use of alternative communication protocols</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-11</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6289
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'Does the organization identify alternative sources of information for organization-defined essential functions and services and use alternative information source for the execution of essential functions or services on organization-defined systems or system components when the primary source of information is corrupted or unavailable?', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> identifying and using alternative information source that is necessary for a mission critical service to operate will allow the service to continue to operate when the primary source of information is not available. Use of information from different sources can also reveal adversary injection or modification.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if alternative sources of information necessary for the delivery of the mission critical service have been identified and are being used by the organization if the primary information source has been corrupted or is unavailable.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><span>Actions taken by a system service or function are often driven by the information it receives. Corruption, fabrication, modification, or deletion of that information could impact the ability of the service function to properly carry out its intended actions.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>By having multiple sources of input, the service or function can continue operation if one source is corrupted or no longer available. Use multiple sources for the same information when possible.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>It is possible that the alternative sources of information may be less precise or less accurate than the primary source of information. But having such sub-optimal information sources may still provide a sufficient level of quality that the essential service or function can be carried out, even in a degraded or debilitated manner.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Alternative sources for all key information assets that are required for the delivery of the mission critical service or high value system have been identified</li>&#10;    <li>And, those alternative sources of key information assets are actively being used when necessary.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Alternative sources for some key information assets that are required for the delivery of the mission critical service or high value system have been identified and are being used when necessary</li>&#10;    <li>Or, alternative sources for all key information assets that are required for the delivery of the mission critical service or high value system have been identified but only some of those sources are available to be used when necessary.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>A documented list of alternative sources for all key information assets required for the delivery of the service.</li>&#10;    <li>Setup documentation showing that the alternate sources are in place and available for use in a time of stress.</li>&#10;    <li>Implementation procedures showing how the alternate sources of information assets would be integrated into the system architecture when needed.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SI-22</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6290
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Title]=N'Deleted', [Question_Text]=N'DELETED QUESTION', [Supplemental_Info]=N'' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6291
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Different designs employed for organization-defined critical systems or system components can present different attack surfaces and thereby enhance the resilience of the mission critical business service.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if an organization employs different designs for organization-defined critical systems or system components in support of presenting different attack surfaces.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><span>Within the context of a given architecture, parallel design teams can solve the same problem in different ways, thus producing different attack surfaces.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Design diversity is achieved by supplying the same requirements specification to multiple developers, each of whom is responsible for developing a variant of the system or system component that meets the requirements.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Variants can be in software design, in hardware design, or in both hardware and a software design.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Hardware design diversity includes making different decisions about what information to keep in analog form and what information to convert to digital form, transmitting the same information at different times, and introducing delays in sampling (temporal diversity).&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Design diversity is commonly used to support fault tolerance.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has documented and employed the use of different designs for organization-defined critical systems or system components.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization is in the process of documenting and employing the use of different designs for organization-defined critical systems or system components.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Design documentation</li>&#10;    <li>Implementation documentation showing the use of alternate designs.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SI-22</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6292
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> The use of alternate authentication factors improves the availability of the mission critical service for a valid user by allowing a user who has inadvertently been locked out to use additional authentication factors to bypass the lockout.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if alternate authentication factors are in use to assist users who have inadvertently been locked out of their accounts.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><span>The use of alternate authentication factors supports the objective of availability and allows a user who has inadvertently been locked out to use additional authentication factors to bypass the lockout.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization has implemented additional authentication factors that are different from the primary authentication factors</li>&#10;    <li>And, the additional authentication factors are employed when number of organization-defined consecutive invalid logon attempts have been exceeded</li>&#10;    <li>And, the organization enforces a limit on the number of consecutive invalid logon attempts during an organization-defined time period.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization is in the process of implementing additional authentication factors that are different from the primary authentication factors</li>&#10;    <li>Or, the organization has implemented additional authentication factors, but the organization does not enforce a limit on the number of consecutive invalid logon attempts</li>&#10;    <li>Or, the organization does enforce a limit of consecutive invalid logon attempts during an organization-defined time period but has not implemented additional authentication factors.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Configuration documentation showing the enforcement of a limit for consecutive invalid logon attempts.</li>&#10;    <li>Configuration documentation showing the establishment and use of alternate authentication factors after the limit of consecutive invalid logon attempts has been reached.</li>&#10;    <li>Examples of each that may have been found in regular reviews for items such as excessive invalid logion attempts.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: AC-7(4)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6293
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'Does the organization Implement multi-factor authentication for local, network, or remote access to  privileged accounts; non-privileged accounts such that:<br/>(a) One of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system gaining access; and<br/>(b) The device meets organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements.', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Regardless of the type of access (i.e., local, network, remote), privileged and non-privileged accounts are authenticated using multi-factor options appropriate for the level of risk. Implementing one of the factors on a separate device (e.g., a hardware token), provides a greater strength of mechanism and an increased level of assurance in the authentication process.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if one of the factors in the organizations multi-factor authentication process is provided by a device separate from the system to which the user is attempting to gain access (e.g., a hardware token).</p>&#10;<p><span>The purpose of requiring a device that is separate from the system to which the user is attempting to gain access for one of the factors during multi-factor authentication is to reduce the likelihood of compromising authenticators or credentials stored on the system.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Adversaries may be able to compromise such authenticators or credentials and subsequently impersonate authorized users.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>For both privileged and non-privileged accounts, the organization&#8217;s multi-factor authentication process for local, network and remote access ensures that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system to which the user is attempting to gain access</li>&#10;    <li>And, the device meets organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization is in the process of implementing a multi-factor authentication process for local, network and remote access that ensures that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system to which the user is attempting to gain access.</li>&#10;    <li>Or, the multi-factor authentication process (that ensures that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system to which the user is attempting to gain access) exists and is only applied to either privileged or non-privileged accounts but not both.</li>&#10;    <li>Or, the multi-factor authentication process that ensures that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system to which the user is attempting to gain access) exists but does not meet organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements.&#160;</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Configuration documentation detailing the multi-factor authentication process and setup and showing that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system to which the user is attempting to gain access.</li>&#10;    <li>Configuration documentation detailing that the separate authentication device meets organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IA-2(6)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6294
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Out-of-band authentication can be used to provide increased levels of security. For example, out-of-band authentication can be used to mitigate actual or suspected man-in the-middle attacks.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization implements out-of-band authentication mechanisms to authenticate users or devices to an information system.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><span>Out-of-band authentication refers to the use of two separate communication paths to identify and authenticate users or devices to an information system.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The first path (i.e., the in-band path) is used to identify and authenticate users or devices and is generally the path through which information flows. The second path (i.e., the out-of-band path) is used to independently verify the authentication and/or requested action.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>For example, a user authenticates via a notebook computer to a remote server to which the user desires access and requests some action of the server via that communication path. Subsequently, the server contacts the user via the user&#8217;s cell phone to verify that the requested action originated from the user. The user may confirm the intended action to an individual on the telephone or provide an authentication code via the telephone.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization implements out-of-band authentication mechanisms to authenticate users or devices to all designated critical service assets or high value information system assets as appropriate.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization implements out-of-band authentication mechanisms to authenticate users or devices to some designated critical service assets or high value information system assets as appropriate.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Configuration documentation detailing the out-of-band authentication mechanisms setup and showing that it is in place and used for controlling access.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IA-2(13)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6295
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> To improve security, organizations may employ out-of-band channels in the delivery or transmission of organizational items, including authenticators and credentials; cryptographic key management information; system and data backups; etc. &#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent</span></strong>: This question determines if<strong><span>&#160;</span></strong>the organization employs out-of-band channels for the physical delivery or electronic transmission of organization-defined information, system components, or devices to organization-defined individuals or systems.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><span>Out-of-band channels include local, non-network accesses to systems; network paths physically separate from network paths used for operational traffic; or non-electronic paths, such as the U.S. Postal Service.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The use of out-of-band channels is contrasted with the use of in-band channels (i.e., the same channels) that carry routine operational traffic. Out-of-band channels do not have the same vulnerability or exposure as in-band channels. Therefore, the confidentiality, integrity, or availability compromises of in-band channels will not compromise or adversely affect the out-of-band channels.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Organizations may employ out-of-band channels in the delivery or transmission of organizational items, including authenticators and credentials; cryptographic key management information; system and data backups; configuration management changes for hardware, firmware, or software; security updates; maintenance information; and malicious code protection updates.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has implemented and is employing out-of-band channels for the physical delivery or electronic transmission of organization-defined information, system components, or devices to organization-defined individuals or systems.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization is in the process of implementing out-of-band channels for the physical delivery or electronic transmission of organization-defined information, system components, or devices.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Documented process showing the setup and use of out-of-band channels for the physical delivery or electronic transmission of organization-defined information, system components, or devices to organization-defined individuals or systems.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SC-37</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6296
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Alternate communications paths reduce the risk of all communications paths being affected by the same incident.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if alternate communications paths for system operations organizational command and control have been implemented and are in use by the organization.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><span>An incident, whether adversarial or non-adversarial based, can disrupt established communications paths used for system operations and organizational command and control. Alternate communications paths reduce the risk of all communications paths being affected by the same incident.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The inability of organizational officials to obtain timely information about disruptions or to provide timely direction to operational elements after a communications path incident, can impact the ability of the organization to respond to such incidents in a timely manner.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Establishing alternate communications paths for command-and-control purposes, including designating alternative decision makers if primary decision makers are unavailable and establishing the extent and limitations of their actions, can greatly facilitate the organization&#8217;s ability to continue to operate and take appropriate actions during an incident.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Alternate communications paths have been documented and implemented and are in use for system operations organizational command and control.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Alternate communications paths are under development and are in the process of being documented and implemented.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Configuration documentation detailing the implantation of the alternate communications paths</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SC-47</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6297
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> The dependence on products, systems, and services from external providers, as well as the nature of the relationships with those providers, present an increasing level of risk to an organization. Threat actions that may increase security or privacy risks include unauthorized production, the insertion or use of counterfeits, tampering, theft, insertion of malicious software and hardware, and poor manufacturing and development practices in the supply chain.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization has developed and documented a plan for managing supply chain risk and if the plan is updated on a scheduled basis.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><span>Supply chain risks can be endemic or systemic within a system element or component, a system, an organization, a sector, or the Nation.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Supply chain risk management (SCRM) activities include identifying and assessing risks, determining appropriate risk response actions, developing SCRM plans to document response actions, and monitoring performance against plans.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The SCRM plan (at the system-level) is implementation specific, providing policy implementation, requirements, constraints, and implications.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The SCRM plan can either be stand-alone or incorporated into system security and privacy plans. The SCRM plan addresses managing, implementation, and monitoring of SCRM controls and the development/sustainment of systems across the SDLC to support mission and business functions.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Because supply chains can differ significantly across and within organizations, SCRM plans are tailored to the individual program, organizational, and operational contexts. Tailored SCRM plans provide the basis for determining whether a technology, service, system component, or system is fit for purpose and, as such, the controls need to be tailored accordingly. Tailored SCRM plans help organizations focus their resources on the most critical mission and business functions based on mission and business requirements and their risk environment.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Supply chain risk management plans include an expression of the supply chain risk tolerance for the organization, acceptable supply chain risk mitigation strategies or controls, a process for consistently evaluating and monitoring supply chain risk, approaches for implementing and communicating the plan, a description of and justification for supply chain risk mitigation measures taken, and associated roles and responsibilities.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Supply chain risk management plans address requirements for developing trustworthy, secure, privacy-protective, and resilient system components and systems, including the application of the security design principles implemented as part of life cycle-based systems security engineering processes (see SA-8).</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>There is documented supply chain risk (SCRM) management for the critical service or HVA system assets.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The plan is in development and partially documented.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Documented SCRM Plan</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SR-2</li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-172: 3.11.7e</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6298
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Diversifying the supply of systems, system components, and services can reduce the impact of a supply chain event or compromise.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization require a diverse set of sources for organizational systems, system components, and services.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><span>Diversifying the supply of systems, system components, and services can reduce the probability that adversaries will successfully identify and target the supply chain and can reduce the impact of a supply chain event or compromise.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Identifying multiple suppliers for replacement components can reduce the probability that the replacement component will become unavailable.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Employing a diverse set of developers or logistics service providers can reduce the impact of a natural disaster or other supply chain event.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has established and documented a diverse set of sources for organizational systems, system components, and services.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>A diverse set of sources for organizational systems, system components, and services is in development and partially documented.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>A documented list of diverse sources for organizational systems, system components and services.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SR-3(1)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6299
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Weaknesses or deficiencies in supply chain elements or processes represent potential vulnerabilities that can be exploited by adversaries to cause harm to the organization and affect its ability to carry out its core missions or business functions.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization takes measures or implements controls to limit the harm from the organization&#8217;s supply chain.&#160;</p>&#10;<p><span>Controls that can be implemented to reduce the probability of adversaries successfully identifying and targeting the supply chain include:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>avoiding the purchase of custom or non-standardized configurations,&#160;</li>&#10;    <li>employing approved vendor lists with standing reputations in industry&#160;</li>&#10;    <li>following pre-agreed maintenance schedules and update and patch delivery mechanisms,</li>&#10;    <li>maintaining a contingency plan in case of a supply chain event,&#160;</li>&#10;    <li>using procurement carve-outs that provide exclusions to commitments or obligations,&#160;</li>&#10;    <li>using diverse delivery routes,&#160;</li>&#10;    <li>minimizing the time between purchase decisions and delivery.&#160;</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has documented and implemented measures (controls) to limit harm from the organization&#8217;s supply chain.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has documented and implemented some measures (controls) to limit harm from the organization&#8217;s supply chain.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>A list of supply chain related controls and associated documentation or configuration information.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SR-3(2)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6300
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Adversaries can attempt to impede organizational operations by disrupting the supply of critical system components or corrupting supplier operations.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization identifies critical system components and takes measures to ensure the adequate supply of those components&#160;</p>&#10;<p><span>The results from a supply chain risk assessment can guide and inform the strategies, tools, and methods that are most applicable to the situation.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Organizations may track systems and component mean time to failure to mitigate the loss of temporary or permanent system function.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Controls to ensure that adequate supplies of critical system components include:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>the use of multiple suppliers throughout the supply chain for the identified critical components</li>&#10;    <li>stockpiling spare components to ensure operation during mission-critical times</li>&#10;    <li>the identification of functionally identical or similar components that may be used, if necessary.</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has documented and implemented measures (controls) to ensure an adequate supply of critical system components.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has documented and implemented some measures (controls) to ensure an adequate supply of critical system components.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>A list of supply chain related controls and associated documentation related to ensuring an adequate supply of critical system components.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SR-5(1)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6301
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> The ability to dynamically reconfigure system components, as part of an incident response capability, demonstrates a high level of organizational maturity.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> Is the organization mature enough to plan and deploy a solution that dynamically reconfigures system components? What are some examples of how system components might be reconfigured in response to an incident?</p>&#10;<p><span>Definition of key words with any examples</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Dynamic Reconfiguration:</span></strong> Changes to router rules, access control lists, intrusion detection or prevention system parameters, and filter rules for guards or firewalls.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization utilizes dynamic reconfiguration as part of its incident response capability. This capability is documented in a strategy or policy. The document should include the specific time frames for achieving the reconfiguration of systems.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization has planned for and/or acquired a dynamic configuration capability but the capability is not in use.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Documents, e.g., a strategy, plan, policy, or concept of operations that describes the dynamic reconfiguration capability.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>IR-4(2)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6302
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> <span>Adversaries may take various paths and use different approaches as they move laterally through an organization (including its systems) to reach their target or as they attempt to exfiltrate information from the organization. The organization often only has a limited set of monitoring and detection capabilities, and they may be focused on the critical or likely infiltration or exfiltration paths. By using communications paths that the organization typically does not monitor, the adversary can increase its chances of achieving its desired goals. By relocating its sensors or monitoring capabilities to new locations, the organization can impede the adversary&#8217;s ability to achieve its goals. The relocation of the sensors or monitoring capabilities might be done based on threat information that the organization has acquired or randomly to confuse the adversary and make its lateral transition through the system or organization more challenging.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Does threat intelligence inform the planning and execution of information security continuous monitoring. Does the organization deploy sensors based to specific locations based on expected adversary activities?</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization relocates sensors and monitoring capabilities to different network locations based on available threat intelligence and in accordance with strategy, policy, or procedures.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization is developing strategy, policy, or procedures to relocate sensors and monitoring capabilities to different network locations based on conditions or circumstances.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Network diagrams and/or strategy, policy, or procedures describing the relocation of sensors or monitoring capabilities based on conditions or circumstances.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>SC-48, SC-48(1)</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6303
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance</span></strong>: Changing the location of cyber resources, systems, and components makes adversary discovery and mapping more difficult.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> Does the organization securely move cyber resources, systems, and/or components or distribute functions across multiple components in order to make it more difficult for adversaries to discover and/or map resources or network infrastructure and to minimize data exposure?</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has a documented policy, plan, or procedure that describes the secure movement of cyber resources, systems, and/or components.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>Organizational personnel can describe the secure movement of cyber resources, systems, and/or components.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Network diagrams that show primary and alternate locations for cyber resources, systems and/or components or distributed systems; strategy, plans, concepts of operation, policies, or procedures for executing the secure movement of cyber resources, systems, and/or components.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>SA-5</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6305
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Title]=N'DELETED', [Question_Text]=N'DELETED QUESTION', [Supplemental_Info]=N'' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6306
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> The principle of secure distributed composition states that the composition of distributed components that enforce the same system security policy result in a system that enforces that policy at least as well as the individual components do. Many of the design principles for secure systems deal with how components can or should interact. The need to create or enable a capability from the composition of distributed components can magnify the relevancy of these principles. In particular, the translation of security policy from a stand-alone to a distributed system or a system-of-systems can have unexpected or emergent results. Communication protocols and distributed data consistency mechanisms help to ensure consistent policy enforcement across a distributed system. To ensure a system-wide level of assurance of correct policy enforcement, the security architecture of a distributed composite system is thoroughly analyzed.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization has implemented the security design principle of secure distributed composition, as required, for systems or system components.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>For systems or system components where the principle of secure distributed composition is applicable, the organization has conducted a thorough analysis of the security architecture to ensure that individually, and collectively, the system components enforce a defined security policy. This analysis, along with relevant control implementation details, should be documented in a System Security Plan (SSP) or similar document.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization has conducted a preliminary analysis of the security architecture but has not implemented the relevant controls to ensure that individually, and collectively, the system components enforce a defined security policy.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>Documented security architecture analysis and relevant control implementation details.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SA-8(17)</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6307
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Distributing processing and storage across multiple physical locations or logical domains provides a degree of redundancy or overlap for organizations. The redundancy and overlap increase the work factor of adversaries to adversely impact organizational operations, assets, and individuals. The use of distributed processing and storage does not assume a single primary processing or storage location. Therefore, it allows for parallel processing and storage.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization distributes processing and storage components across multiple physical locations and logical domains.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization distributes processing and storage across multiple physical locations or logical domains in accordance with a strategy, plan, concept of operation, or policy. As applicable, the specific implementation details are documented in a System Security Plan (SSP).</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>The organization distributes processing and storage across multiple physical location or logical domains but has not documented its approach or the specific implementation details in a System Security Plan (SSP).</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>An organizational strategy, plan, concept of operation, or policy. As applicable, specific implementation details in a System Security Plan (SSP).</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SC-36</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6308
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizations should have a documented policy for asset management as it establishes organizational expectations for planning and performing the asset management process and it also communicates those expectations to the organization.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if a policy for performing asset management activities exists.</p>&#10;<p><span>A policy is a written communication from the organization&#8217;s senior management to employees.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The asset management policy should address:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>responsibility, authority, ownership, and the requirement to perform asset management activities</li>&#10;    <li>establishment of procedures, standards, and guidelines</li>&#10;    <li>establishing and maintaining an asset inventory</li>&#10;    <li>managing access to assets</li>&#10;    <li>categorizing, safeguarding, and disposing of information assets</li>&#10;    <li>measuring adherence to policy, exceptions granted, and policy violations</li>&#10;    <li>compliance with legal, regulatory, contractual, and government obligations</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has a documented policy for performing asset management.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>A policy is in development and partially documented.</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A Standard Operating Procedure for Asset Management or Other relevant organizational policy covering asset management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: AM:MIL2.Q2</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CM-1</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6309
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizations should have a documented policy for controls management as it establishes the organizational expectations for planning and performing the controls management process as well as communicates those expectations to the organization.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if a policy for performing controls management activities exists.</p>&#10;<p><span>A policy is a written communication from the organization&#8217;s senior management to employees.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The controls management policy should address:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>responsibility, authority, ownership, and the requirement to perform controls management activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>establishment of procedures, standards, and guidelines</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>requirements for periodically assessing the control environment</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>measuring adherence to policy, exceptions granted, and policy violations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>compliance with legal, regulatory, contractual, and government obligations</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has a documented policy for performing controls management.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>A policy is in development and partially documented</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A Standard Operating Procedure for Controls Management or Other relevant organizational policy covering controls management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: CM:MIL2.Q2</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SC-1, SI-1, AC-1</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6310
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizations should have a documented policy for change management as it establishes the organizational expectations for planning and performing the change management process as well as communicates those expectations to the organization.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if a policy for performing change management activities exists.</p>&#10;<p><span>A policy is a written communication from the organization&#8217;s senior management to employees.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The change management policy should address:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>responsibility, authority, ownership, and the requirement to perform change management activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>establishment of procedures, standards, and guidelines</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Requesting and approving changes to assets</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>measuring adherence to policy, exceptions granted, and policy violations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>compliance with legal, regulatory, contractual, and government obligations</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li>The organization has a documented policy for performing change management.</li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li>A policy is in development and partially documented</li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A Standard Operating Procedure for Change Management or Other relevant organizational policy</span><span>&#160;covering change management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: CCM:MIL2.Q2</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CM-1</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6311
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizations should have a documented policy for vulnerability management as it establishes the organizational expectations for planning and performing the vulnerability management process as well as communicates those expectations to the organization.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> This question determines if a policy for performing vulnerability management activities exists.</p>&#10;<p><span>A policy is a written communication from the organization&#8217;s senior management to employees.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The vulnerability management policy should address:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>responsibility, authority, ownership, and the requirement to perform vulnerability management activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>establishment of procedures, standards, and guidelines</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>requirements for periodically assessing the vulnerability management activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>measuring adherence to policy, exceptions granted, and policy violations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>compliance with legal, regulatory, contractual, and government obligations</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a documented policy for performing vulnerability management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>A policy is in development and partially documented</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)&#160;</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A Standard Operating Procedure for vulnerability Management or Other relevant organizational policy covering vulnerability management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: VM:MIL2.Q2</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: RA-1, RA-5</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6312
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizations should have a documented policy for incident management as such a policy establishes the organizational expectations for planning and performing the incident management process and communicates those expectations to the organization.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if a policy for performing incident management activities exists.</p>&#10;<p><span>A policy is a written communication from the organization&#8217;s senior management to its employees.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The policy should address:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>responsibility, authority, ownership, and the requirement to perform incident management activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>establishment of procedures, standards, and guidelines</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>requirements for periodically assessing incident management activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>post-incident review, problem resolution, and closure</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>measuring adherence to policy, exceptions granted, and policy violations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>compliance with legal, regulatory, contractual, and government obligations</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a documented policy for performing incident management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>A policy is in development and partially documented.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>&#160;A Standard Operating Procedure for Incident Management or Other relevant organizational policy covering incident management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR:&#160;</span><a href="IM%3AMIL2.Q2"><span>IM:MIL2.Q2</span></a></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IR-1</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6313
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizations should have a documented policy for service continuity management as it establishes the organizational expectations for planning and performing the service continuity management process and communicates those expectations to the organization.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if a policy for performing service continuity management activities exists.</p>&#10;<p><span>A policy is a written communication from the organization&#8217;s senior management to employees.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The policy should address:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>responsibility, authority, ownership, and the requirement to perform service continuity management activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>establishment of procedures, standards, and guidelines</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>requirements for periodically assessing the service continuity management activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>communication of plans to stakeholders</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>responsibility for testing plans on a regular basis</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>measuring adherence to policy, exceptions granted, and policy violations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>compliance with legal, regulatory, contractual, and government obligations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>post-plan review and revision</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a documented policy for performing service continuity management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A Standard Operating Procedure for Service Continuity Management or Other relevant organizational policy covering service continuity management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: SCM:MIL2.Q2</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-1, MA-1</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6314
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizations should have a documented policy for risk management as it <strong><span>establishes the organizational expectations&#160;</span></strong><span>for planning and performing the risk management process and <strong><span>communicates those expectations&#160;</span></strong>to the organization.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if a policy for performing risk management activities exists.</p>&#10;<p><span>A policy is a written communication from the organization&#8217;s senior management to employees.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The policy should address:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>responsibility, authority, ownership, and the requirement to perform risk management activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>establishment of procedures, standards, and guidelines</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>requirements for periodically assessing the risk environment</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>measuring adherence to policy, when exceptions are granted, and policy violations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>compliance with legal, regulatory, contractual, and government obligations</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a documented policy for performing risk management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>A policy is in development and partially documented.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)&#160;</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A Standard Operating Procedure for Risk Management or Other relevant organizational policy covering risk management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: RM:MIL2.Q2</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: RA-1, SR-1</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6315
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:&#160;</span></strong>Organizations should have a policy for external dependencies management as it establishes the organizational expectations for planning and performing the external dependencies management process and communicates those expectations to the organization.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if a policy for performing external dependency management activities exists.</p>&#10;<p><span>A policy is a written communication from the organization&#8217;s senior management to employees.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The policy should address:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>responsibility, authority, ownership, and the requirement to perform external dependency management activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>establishment of procedures, standards, and guidelines</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>requirements for periodically assessing the external dependency management activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>requesting, approving, providing, and terminating access for external entities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>requesting, approving, providing, and terminating agreements with external entities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>measuring adherence to policy, exceptions granted, and policy violations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>compliance with legal, regulatory, contractual, and government obligation.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a documented policy for performing external dependency management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>A policy is in development and partially documented.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A Standard Operating Procedure for External Dependencies Management or Other relevant organizational policy covering External Dependencies management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: EDM:MIL2.Q2</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SR-1, SA-1</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6316
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> <span>Organizations should have a documented policy for training as it <strong><span>establishes the organizational expectations&#160;</span></strong>for planning and performing the training process and <strong><span>communicates those expectations&#160;</span></strong>to the organization.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> This question determines if a policy for performing training activities exists.</p>&#10;<p><span>A policy is a written communication from the organization&#8217;s senior management to employees.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The policy should address:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>responsibility, authority, ownership, and the requirement to perform training activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>establishment of procedures, standards, and guidelines</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>requirements for periodically assessing training effectiveness</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>measuring adherence to policy, exceptions granted, and policy violations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>compliance with legal, regulatory, contractual, and government obligations</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a documented policy for performing training.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>A policy is in development and partially documented.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A Standard Operating Procedure for training or other relevant organizational policy covering training.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: TA:MIL2.Q2</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: AT-1, PS-1</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6317
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> <span>Organizations should have a documented policy for situational awareness as it <strong><span>establishes the organizational expectations&#160;</span></strong>for planning and performing the situational awareness process and <strong><span>communicates those expectations&#160;</span></strong>to the organization.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if a <strong><span>policy for performing&#160;</span></strong>situational awareness activities <strong><span>exists</span></strong>.</p>&#10;<p><span>A policy is a written communication from the organization&#8217;s senior management to employees.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>The policy should address:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>responsibility, authority, ownership, and the requirement to perform situational awareness activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>establishment of procedures, standards, and guidelines</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>approving threat communication methods and channels</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>measuring adherence to policy, exceptions granted, and policy violations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>compliance with legal, regulatory, contractual, and government obligations</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a documented policy for performing situational awareness.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>A policy is in development and partially documented.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>&#160;A Standard Operating Procedure for situational awareness or other relevant organizational policy covering situational awareness.&#160;</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: SA:MIL2.Q2</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: AT-1, PS-1</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6318
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizations should define and document policy on data retention to help manage the risk associated with data storage. This is especially critical if the organization is subject to regulations that require data to be retained for specified duration.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization defines a data retention policy.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a documented data retention policy.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>No partial implementation is considered for this capability.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A documented data retention policy or portion of another policy document that included data retention</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>IMCA: 1.2.2.06.</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: PT-1, SI-1, MP-1</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6319
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Having a documented continuous monitoring strategy allows for management to review processes for adherence to and deviations from their intended performance and effectiveness levels.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization has a continuous monitoring strategy and policy and to determine how that strategy is implemented.</p>&#10;<p><span>Continuous monitoring is the practice of maintaining ongoing awareness of information security, vulnerabilities, and threats to support organizational risk management decisions.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a fully documented continuous monitoring strategy and/or policy and has processes in place to facilitate that strategy.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The organization is in the process of creating a continuous monitoring strategy or policy</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, the organization has a continuous monitoring strategy/policy, however it is not yet embedded into the organization&#8217;s business functions.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Documentation for continuous monitoring strategy or policy, organizational security tools or processes that implement and automate continuous monitoring functions.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>HVA: CM:PROCESS.Q1</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CA-7</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6320
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> An organizational System Development Life Cycle policy can be broad and cover the entire organization, or they can be tailored by individual teams or business units to fit specific requirements.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question seeks to understand the level of specificity in the System Development Life Cycle (SDLC) used in the organization. It looks to clarify if the SDLC policy is enforced at an enterprise level or if there are separate processes used at lower levels within the organization.</p>&#10;<p><span>The level at which the policy is created can determine how specific the process gets, so this question seeks to understand the level of standardization provided by the SDLC.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a fully documented Enterprise level System Development Life Cycle (SDLC) program/policy that is standardized and repeatable for broad use throughout the organization.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The organization has a partially documented Enterprise level System Development Life Cycle (SDLC) program/policy that is standardized and repeatable for broad use throughout the organization.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, the organization has a System Development Life Cycle (SDLC) program/policy, however it is not enforced at the enterprise level.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>System Development Life Cycle (SDLC) program/policy documentation</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>HVA: DEPENDENCIES:LCM.Q1&#160;</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SA-1, SR-2</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6321
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizations should have information disclosure policies in place to ensure that personnel are educated on data classification standards within the organization</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization has an information disclosure policy that sufficiently details dissemination guidance for organizational information.</p>&#10;<p><span>If personnel are uneducated on information disclosure processes, accidental disclosure introduces significant risk to the organization. Therefore, organizations should create formal documentation that describes an information disclosure policy or specific guidance. This policy should include information regarding what kind of data and information is allowed to be disclosed as well as detail information regarding any waiting periods or timeframes as to when disclosure should occur.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a fully documented information disclosure policy that describes what information can be distributed to whom and in what timeframe.&#160;</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The organization has a partially documented information disclosure policy</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)&#160;</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Formal documentation for the information disclosure policy or guidance</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>IMCA: 1.2.2.04</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: CP-1</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6322
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> organizations should have media relations policy or guidance in place to avoid the accidental disclosure of sensitive information for organizational incidents or vulnerabilities.</p>&#10;&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization has established a media relations or guidance to be used when organizational personnel are faced with questions, calls, or other interactions from the media.</p>&#10;&#10;<p><span>Organizations can suffer reputationally if public and media relations are not properly managed in the aftermath of an organizational incident. Media relations policies or guidance help organizational personnel navigate press and media inquiries while incidents are occurring.</span></p>&#10;&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong><span>&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;</span></p><div><ul><li><span>The organization has a fully documented media or public relations policy that informs organizational personnel how to respond to questions, calls, and other inquiries from the media in the event of an organizational cyber incident.</span></li></ul>&#10;&#10;</div>&#10;&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p><ul><li><span>The organization has a partially documented media or public relations policy that informs organizational personnel how to respond to questions, calls, and other inquiries from the media in the event of an organizational cyber incident.</span></li>&#10;&#10;&#160; &#160; <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;&#10;</ul>&#10;&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong><span>&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;&#160;</span></p><div><ul><li><span>Documented media or public relations policy</span></li></ul></div><p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;&#10;&#160; &#160; <li><span>IMCA: 1.2.2.03</span></li>&#10;&#10;&#160; &#160; <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IR-1, IR-4(15)</li>&#10;&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6323
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Personnel should be able to access and reference organizational policies and procedures, if an employee is unsure as to whether they are acting in accordance with organizational policy, it should be easily referenceable so they may be informed.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>Organizational should be able to access and reference organizational policies and procedures, one component of this is informing employees where such documentation is located. This would likely be addressed in training and/or the onboarding process.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>All organizational personnel are aware of the location where written organizational policy is located and this information is conveyed via mandatory training.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Most organizational personnel are aware of the location where written organizational policy is located and this information is conveyed via training.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Verbal attestation from organizational personnel regarding where the organizational policy lives and confirmation that they are able to access it.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>IMCA: 4.2</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: All -1 controls from all security control families. As all policies are covered by this question.</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6324
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Policies and procedures should be kept current to accurately reflect the organizational cybersecurity posture and strategy.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question understand if policies and procedures are updated appropriately.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>All organizational policies and procedures are reviewed at the organization-defined</span><span>&#160;frequency.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Some organizational policies and procedures are reviewed at the organization-defined frequency</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, organizational policies and procedures are reviewed, however on an infrequent basis.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Document revision or review history for policies and procedures,</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>IMCA: 4.2</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: All -1 controls from all security control families. As all policies are covered by this question.</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6325
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Text]=N'Is there a defined process for communicating changes and revisions to policy throughout relevant parts of the organization?', [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizational personnel should be informed of relevant changes and revisions to policy so they can abide by it.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization has a defined process in place to notify affected personnel of changes to organizational policy.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a fully documented and defined process for notifying employees and specific business units of relevant changes or revisions to policy.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization notifies personnel of changes to policy, however the process by which notifications regarding such changes are disseminated to appropriate personnel are not standardized or fully documented.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Correspondence showing a standard notification received by organizational personnel when updates have been made to policy, documentation describing the procedures for notification when changes to policy are made.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>IMCA: 4.2</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: All -1 controls from all security control families. As all policies are covered by this question.</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6326
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Organizational plans should be reviewed at a minimum annually to ensure they are kept current.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines whether organizational plans and policies pertaining to incident management are reviewed at least once a year to identify and implement updates. &#160;</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization reviews all of its policies and plans pertaining to incident management at least once a year to identify and implement updates.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The organization reviews some of its policies and plans pertaining to incident management at least once a year to identify and implement updates.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Document review history or correspondence that substantiates review activities have occurred at least yearly for organizational incident management plans and policies.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>IMCA: 1.2.2.12 Quality.</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6327
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Security Risk Assessments should be conducted to comply with organization policy as well as any regulatory requirements the organization is subject to. To adequately perform such assessments, there should be a policy standardizing the way they are conducted.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization has a documented policy or guidance for the performance of security risk assessments.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a fully documented policy or guidance that standardizes the way the organization conducts security risk assessments.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The organization has a partially documented policy or guidance for conducting security risk assessments.</span></li>&#10;    <li>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Organizational policy or standard operating procedure for conducting security risk assessments</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>IMCA: 2.1.1.02 Control</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: RA-1</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6328
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Operational exercises to test the effectiveness of organizational policy and procedures should be conducted at least annually.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization has a documented policy or guidance exists that requires periodic (at least annual) operational exercises.</p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has a fully documented policy or guidance that requires periodic (at least annual) operational exercises.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The organization has a partially documented policy or guidance that requires periodic (at least annual) operational exercises to be conducted.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, the organization has documented policy or guidance though it does not require operational exercises to be conducted at least annually.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Organizational policy documents</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>IMCA: 2.3.1.02 Control</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6329
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:&#160;</span></strong><span>Stakeholders are more likely to be invested in asset management activities when they are well informed and aware of their roles in the process.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> This question determines if stakeholders for asset management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</p>&#10;<p><span>Stakeholders of the asset management process have the following responsibilities:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>creating an asset inventory baseline</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>associating assets with the critical service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>overseeing the asset management process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>managing the risk resulting from unresolved problems (gaps in the inventory of asset protection and sustainment requirements, insufficient staffing, or funding, etc.)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>Examples of stakeholders include:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>critical service owners</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>asset management staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>owners and custodians of assets that underpin the service (to include facility security personnel)</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>critical service staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>external entities responsible for some part of the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>information technology staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>human resources</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>internal and external auditors</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>All stakeholders for the asset management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Some stakeholders for the asset management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, stakeholders are identified but have not been made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)&#160;</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>A Standard Operating Procedure for asset management or other relevant organizational policy that includes a section on roles and responsibilities for asset management functions</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: AM:MIL2.Q3</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6330
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> <span>Stakeholders are more likely to be invested in controls management activities when they are well informed and aware of their roles in the process.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if stakeholders for controls management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</p>&#10;<p><span>Stakeholders of the controls management process have the following responsibilities:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>defining and managing control objectives and controls, including ensuring the effectiveness of controls</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>overseeing the controls management process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>managing the risk resulting from unresolved problems (gaps in controls, insufficient staffing, or funding, etc.)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>Examples of stakeholders include:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>critical service owners</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>management</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>controls management staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>owners and custodians of assets that underpin the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>critical service staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>external entities responsible for some part of the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>information technology staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>staff responsible for physical security</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>human resources</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>internal and external auditors</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>All stakeholders for the controls management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Some stakeholders for the controls management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, stakeholders are identified but have not been made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>&#160;A Standard Operating Procedure for controls management or other relevant organizational policy that includes a section on roles and responsibilities for controls management functions</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: CM:MIL2.Q3</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6331
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> <span>Stakeholders are more likely to be invested in change management activities when they are well informed and aware of their roles in the process.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if stakeholders for change management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</p>&#10;<p><span>Stakeholders of the change management process have the following responsibilities:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>creating asset baselines</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>overseeing the change management process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>capacity management planning</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>configuration management</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>requesting and approving changes to assets</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>resolving issues in the change management process</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>Examples of stakeholders include:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>critical service owners</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>management</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>change management staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>owners and custodians of assets that underpin the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>critical service staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>external entities responsible for some part of the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>information technology staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>staff responsible for physical security</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>human resources</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>internal and external auditors</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>All stakeholders for the change management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Some stakeholders for the change management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, stakeholders are identified but have not been made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>&#160;A Standard Operating Procedure for change management or other relevant organizational policy that includes a section on roles and responsibilities for change management functions</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: CCM:MIL2.Q3</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6332
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> <span>Stakeholders are more likely to be invested in vulnerability management activities when they are well informed and aware of their roles in the process.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>To determine if stakeholders for vulnerability management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</p>&#10;<p><span>Stakeholders of the vulnerability management process have the following responsibilities:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>overseeing the vulnerability management process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>resolving issues with the vulnerability management process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>establishing vulnerability prioritization guidelines</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>assessing collected vulnerability data</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>providing feedback to those responsible for providing vulnerability data</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>reviewing and appraising the effectiveness of vulnerability management activities</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>Examples of stakeholders include:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>critical service owners</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>management</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>owners of external entity relationships</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>vulnerability management program staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>owners and custodians of assets that underpin the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>critical service staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>external entities responsible for some part of the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>information technology staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>staff responsible for physical security</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>human resources</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>internal and external auditors</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>acquisition and procurement staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>enterprise risk management staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>service continuity staff</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>All stakeholders for the vulnerability management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Some stakeholders for the vulnerability management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, stakeholders are identified but have not been made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>&#160;A Standard Operating Procedure for vulnerability management or other relevant organizational policy that includes a section on roles and responsibilities for vulnerability management functions</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: VM:MIL2.Q3</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6333
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong><span>&#160;Stakeholders are more likely to be invested in incident management activities when they are well informed and aware of their roles in the process.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if stakeholders for incident management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</p>&#10;<p><span>Stakeholders of the incident management process have the following responsibilities:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>overseeing the incident management process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>making critical decisions during the incident management process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>resolving issues with the incident management process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>detecting events and incidents</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>planning for incident handling, management, and response</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>collecting, documenting, and preserving event and incident evidence</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>analyzing events and incidents</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>declaring incidents</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>Examples of stakeholders include:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>critical service owners and staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>management</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>incident managers</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>incident owners</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>staff who serve key roles in incident communication activities, such as public relations</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>owners and custodians of assets that underpin the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>external entities responsible for some part of the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>information technology staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>staff responsible for physical security</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>human resources</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>internal and external auditors</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>acquisition and procurement staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>service continuity staff</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>All stakeholders for the incident management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Some stakeholders for the incident management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, stakeholders are identified but have not been made aware of their roles</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>&#160;A Standard Operating Procedure for incident management or other relevant organizational policy that includes a section on roles and responsibilities for incident management functions</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR:&#160;</span><a href="IM%3AMIL2.Q3"><span>IM:MIL2.Q3</span></a></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6334
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> <span>Stakeholders are more likely to be invested in service continuity management activities when they are well informed and aware of their roles in the process.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if stakeholders for service continuity activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</p>&#10;<p><span>Stakeholders of the service continuity management process have the following responsibilities:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>overseeing the service continuity management process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>developing service continuity plans</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>coordinating service continuity activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>participating in the test and execution of service continuity plans</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>resolving issues with the service continuity management process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>ensuring that service continuity plans reflect all external dependencies</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>reviewing and appraising the effectiveness of service continuity activities</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>Examples of stakeholders include:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>critical service owners</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>management</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>owners and custodians of assets that underpin the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>critical service staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>external entities responsible for some part of the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>information technology staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>staff responsible for physical security</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>regulatory and legal entities to which the organization is required to submit service continuity plans</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>internal and external auditors</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>service continuity staff</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>All stakeholders for the service continuity management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Some stakeholders for the service continuity management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, stakeholders are identified but have not been made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>&#160;A Standard Operating Procedure for service continuity management or other relevant organizational policy that includes a section on roles and responsibilities for service continuity management functions</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: SCM:MIL2.Q3</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6335
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> <span>Stakeholders are more likely to be invested in risk management activities when they are well informed and aware of their roles in the process.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Question Intent: This question determines if stakeholders for risk management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Stakeholders of the risk management process have the following responsibilities:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>identifying risk</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>analyzing risk</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>developing and implementing risk mitigation plans</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>reviewing the effectiveness of the risk management process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>managing the risk resulting from unresolved problems (gaps in processes, insufficient staffing, or funding, etc.)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>Examples of stakeholders include:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>critical service owners</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>management</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>owners and custodians of assets that underpin the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>external entities responsible for some part of the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>information technology staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>staff responsible for physical security</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>human resources</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>internal and external auditors</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><strong><span>All&#160;</span></strong><span>stakeholders for the risk management activities have been <strong>identified&#160;</strong>and <strong>made aware&#160;</strong>of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Some stakeholders for the risk management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, stakeholders are identified but have not been made aware of their roles</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>&#160;A Standard Operating Procedure for risk management or other relevant organizational policy that includes a section on roles and responsibilities for risk management functions</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: RM:MIL2.Q3</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6336
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> <span>Stakeholders are more likely to be invested in risk management activities when they are well informed and aware of their roles in the process.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> <span>Stakeholders are more likely to be invested in external dependencies management activities when they are well informed and aware of their roles in the process.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if stakeholders for external dependency activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</p>&#10;<p><span>Stakeholders of the external dependency management process have the following responsibilities:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>overseeing the external dependency management process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>resolving issues with the external dependency management process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>planning for evaluating, selecting, and managing relationships with external entities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>creating and maintaining a prioritized inventory of all external dependencies</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>monitoring the performance of external entities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>ensuring that service continuity plans reflect all external dependencies</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>managing the operational risk that arises from external dependencies</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>Examples of stakeholders include:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>critical service owners</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>management</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>owners of external entity relationships</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>external dependency management program staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>owners and custodians of assets that underpin the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>critical service staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>external entities responsible for some part of the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>information technology staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>staff responsible for physical security</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>human resources</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>internal and external auditors</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>acquisition and procurement staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>service continuity staff</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><strong><span>All&#160;</span></strong><span>stakeholders for external dependencies management activities have been <strong>identified&#160;</strong>and <strong>made aware&#160;</strong>of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span><strong>Some</strong> stakeholders for external dependencies management activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, stakeholders are identified but have not been made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>&#160;A Standard Operating Procedure for external dependencies management or other relevant organizational policy that includes a section on roles and responsibilities for external dependencies management functions</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: EDM:MIL2.Q3</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6337
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> <span>Stakeholders are more likely to be invested in training activities when they are well informed and aware of their roles in the process.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if stakeholders for training activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</p>&#10;<p><span>Stakeholders of the training process have the following responsibilities:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>defining and managing training requirements</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>conducting and overseeing the delivery of training</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>ensuring the effectiveness of training</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>Examples of stakeholders include:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>critical service owners</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>management</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>training staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>owners and custodians of assets that underpin the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>critical service staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>external entities responsible for some part of the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>information technology staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>staff responsible for physical security</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>human resources</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>internal and external auditors</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><strong><span>All&#160;</span></strong><span>stakeholders for training activities have been <strong>identified&#160;</strong>and <strong>made aware&#160;</strong>of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Some stakeholders for training activities have been identified and made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, stakeholders are identified but have not been made aware of their roles.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>&#160;A Standard Operating Procedure for training or other relevant organizational policy that includes a section on roles and responsibilities for training functions</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: TA:MIL2.Q3</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6338
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> <span>Stakeholders are more likely to be invested in situational awareness activities when they are well informed and aware of their roles in the process.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if <strong><span>stakeholders&#160;</span></strong>for situational awareness activities have been <strong><span>identified&#160;</span></strong>and <strong><span>made aware of their roles</span></strong>.</p>&#10;<p><span>Stakeholders of the situational awareness process have the following responsibilities:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>identifying the threat monitoring and communication requirements</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>defining and managing situational awareness activities, including ensuring the effectiveness of those activities</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>overseeing the situational awareness process</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>receiving and responding to threat information</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>Examples of stakeholders include:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>critical service owners</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>management</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>situational awareness staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>owners and custodians of assets that underpin the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>critical service staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>service continuity staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>external entities responsible for some part of the service</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>information technology staff</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>staff responsible for physical security</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>human resources</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><strong><span>All</span></strong><span>&#160;stakeholders for situational awareness activities have been <strong>identified</strong> and <strong>made aware</strong> of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><strong><span>Some</span></strong><span>&#160;stakeholders for situational awareness activities have been <strong>identified</strong> and <strong>made aware</strong> of their roles.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Or, stakeholders are identified but have <strong>not been made aware</strong> of their roles.</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>&#160;A Standard Operating Procedure for situational awareness or other relevant organizational policy that includes a section on roles and responsibilities for situational awareness functions</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR: SA:MIL2.Q3</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6339
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Personnel performing incident management activities should be aware of their roles and responsibilities with regards to the incident management plan. Plans must be reviewed to ensure that roles and responsibilities are appropriately designated.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if<strong><span>&#160;t</span></strong>he incident management plan is reviewed at least yearly to ensure that the roles and responsibilities designated for incident management activities are relevant and appropriate.</p>&#10;<p><span>Organizations may choose to review the incident management plan in accordance with a defined frequency, however it is important to ensure that the plan is also reviewed when personnel with incident management responsibilities leave the organization so their roles and responsibilities can be reassigned to someone else within the organization.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization reviews roles and responsibilities within the incident management plan at least annually as well as when an employee with incident management responsibilities leaves the organization.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The organization reviews roles and responsibilities within the incident management plan, however there is not a defined frequency with which this review occurs.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Document review history or correspondence that substantiates review activities have occurred within the appropriate frequency.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>IMCA: 1.1.3.04</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6340
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Understanding of roles and responsibilities is critical in organizations, specifically pertaining to monitoring, reporting, and collateral security functions when shared between internal roles and external partners.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines how the organization performs monitoring, reporting, and collateral security functions.</p>&#10;<p><span>Many organizations outsource specific security functions, such as digital forensics engagements and 24/7 incident response capabilities. When roles and responsibilities between parties are divided between the internal organization and an external service provider, it is important to have defined expectations for such responsibilities to verify that they are being performed by the expected party, and either incorporate deliberate redundant functions or eliminate redundancy that does not serve a specific purpose.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization documents and defines role and responsibilities between parties for monitoring, reporting, and collateral security functions.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The organization partially defines role and responsibility assignments between parties for monitoring, reporting, and collateral security functions.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>RACI Matrix, Responsibility Assignment Matrix</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>HVA: NETWORK PROTECTIONS:INTERCONNECTIONS:Q5</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: <span>PS-7, PM-1, PM-2</span></li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6341
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Legal and regulatory requirements regarding cybersecurity sometimes have time-based retention requirements, therefore data handling, retention, and disposal should be tracked to comply with such regulations.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if organizational requirements are managed throughout their entire lifecycle.</p>&#10;<p><span>Requirements should be tracked to ensure they are kept current and relevant to the organization. However, there may be special considerations for certain legal and regulatory requirements that organizations also much be aware of.</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization manages all requirements throughout their entire life cycle by using a standardized process to monitor requirements.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The organization manages high-importance requirements throughout their entire life cycle, though not all organizational requirements are tracked.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>&#160;Requirements Traceability Matrix</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>Cyber IST</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: All -1 controls from all security control families, as 1b of each -1 control will address this per each policy.</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6342
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Consistency across multiple supplier contracts can help the acquirer achieve a higher degree of predictability and control among external entities and help to ensure that all suppliers meet at least a minimal level of requirements.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:</span></strong> This question determines if the acquirer has established a set of baseline requirements that apply to all formal agreements with suppliers that support the critical service.</p>&#10;<p><span>Developing baseline requirements normally involves an evaluation of the acquirer&#8217;s enterprise requirements. These are the requirements that the enterprise deems important for every supplier relationship. Regulatory requirements may often form the basis for these. For example, in the medical field, laws to protect the confidentiality of protected health information (PHI) require standard requirements for every third party that stores this information.</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Typical work products:</span></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Standard contract language that includes, for example, reporting, compliance, and flow down requirements</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The acquirer has a documented collection of baseline contractual requirements for suppliers that support the critical service.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>The acquirer has a partially documented collection of baseline contractual requirements for suppliers, or the baseline requirements apply to only some suppliers, or the practice appears otherwise incomplete.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Contracts between the supplier and acquirer.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>EDM: RF:G2.Q2</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: SR-3(3), SA-4</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6343
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Failure to comply with statutory requirements for evidence identification and classification can result in legal ramifications. Therefore, it is critical that organizations abide by the industry-specific, national, regional, and state regulations for the areas in which the organization operates.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if requirements for identifying event evidence for forensic purposes have been identified.</p>&#10;<p><span>An event may become an organizational incident that has the potential to be a violation of local, state, or federal rules, laws, and regulations. For example:</span></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Securities and Exchange Commission regulatory requirements</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>state privacy laws</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>Food and Drug Administration regulatory requirements</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>chain of custody requirements</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><span>This is often not known early in the investigation of an event, so the organization should <strong><span>ensure that all event evidence is handled properly</span></strong></span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>The organization has identified and documented relevant requirements for identifying event evidence for forensic purposes.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>Requirements for identifying event evidence are in development and partially documented.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Incident response plan, Standard Operating Procedure for Incident Management, or Other relevant organizational policy covering incident management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR:&#160;</span><a href="IM%3AG2.Q8"><span>IM:G2.Q8</span></a></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IR-1, IR-8(1), AU-10</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6344
UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Supplemental_Info]=N'<p><strong><span>Importance:</span></strong> Failure to comply with statutory requirements for evidence handling can result in legal ramifications. Therefore, it is critical that organizations abide by the industry-specific, national, regional, and state regulations for the areas in which the organization operates.</p>&#10;<p><strong><span>Question Intent:&#160;</span></strong>This question determines if the organization has implemented a process to ensure event evidence is handled as required by law or other obligations.</p>&#10;<p><span>Based on applicable requirements the organization should develop a process using standards and guidelines for the collection, documentation, and preservation of event evidence.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><span>Staff should be trained on the organizational process for proper identification and handling of evidence to ensure that the evidence is not altered, and that integrity is maintained.&#160;</span></p>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Full Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>There is a documented process to ensure event evidence is handled as required by law or other obligations.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><em><span>Criteria for Partial Implementation Response</span></em></strong></p>&#10;<ul>&#10;    <li><span>A process is in development and partially documented.</span></li>&#10;    <li><span>(Otherwise, the answer is marked as No Implementation)</span></li>&#10;</ul>&#10;<p><strong><span>Possible Evidence</span></strong></p>&#10;<div>&#10;    <ul>&#10;        <li><span>Incident response plan, Standard Operating Procedure for Incident Management, or Other relevant organizational policy covering incident management.</span></li>&#10;    </ul>&#10;</div>&#10;<p><strong><span>Reference to standards/source assessments</span></strong></p>&#10;<ul class="decimal_type">&#10;    <li><span>CRR:&#160;</span><span>IM:G2.Q9</span></li>&#10;    <li>NIST 800-53, Rev. 5: IR-1, IR-8(1), AU-10</li>&#10;</ul>' WHERE [Mat_Question_Id] = 6345
